<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Law-makers Demand President's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Commissioners in Zimbabwe's
Constitutional Review Commission Friday said President Robert
Mugabe must reassure the nation that he will not reject the
constitution that will be produced by the commission.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the commission's plenary session here Friday,
commissioner Lawrence Chakaredza told the Zimbabwe News Agency
that although Mugabe made such an undertaking when the commission
was instituted this May, there was need for him to make a public
reassurance so that people will cooperate with the commissioners.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The people will be more forthcoming if the head of
state makes such a guarantee because it will show that he is
respectful of the commission."
</P>
<P>
"It will be folly for the government to reject what the people
want," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We want the president to pledge that he is not going to
interfere with the constitution we are making," Japa said.
</P>
<P>
Member of Parliament Irene Zindi, who is also a member of the
Constitutional Commission, said the plenary was democratic.
</P>
<P>
She said the commissioners' suggestions were considered and
hoped that people would give the best of ideas which would enable
the drafting of a democratic constitution for Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commissioners were put into small groups of four
each and will start gathering people's views countrywide from
August 16 to September 15 for inclusion into the new constitution.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
