<HEADLINE> U.N. Helps to Demobilize Ex-Fighters in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations military
observers have carried out the temporary registration of 200
ex-combatants in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, a U.N.
spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference that the temporary registration was done by the United
Nations Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL) Military
Observers.
</P>
<P>
"Arrangements are underway for the transfer of Lungi, on the
other side of the estuary, where the complete registration and
disarmament, demobilization, reintegration program will be
conducted," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The three reception sites which had been set up temporarily in
Freetown to cater for the influx of ex-combatants are going to be
closed once they are moved to Lungi, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the United Nations was appealing for 35
million U.S. dollars to finance the disarmament of former rebel
soldiers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Silva said last week that the United Nations was appealing to
donors on behalf of Sierra Leone for an initial 35 million U.S.
dollars to demobilize, disarm and reintegrate the rebel soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
