<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Italian parliament has approved Wednesday the
draft agreement signed in Brussels in 1997 on the phased
establishment of a European Union-Moroccan free trade zone before
the year 2010,
</P>
<P>
Italy was the last EU state to sanction the partnership accord
with Morocco, following the approval by the parliaments of 14 EU
states.
</P>
<P>
Friday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" quoted observers in Rabat as
saying that the agreement with Morocco will be enforced before the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Director of the Yemeni Foundation for Mineral Wealth
and Geological Survey Ismail Al Jund said Yemen plans to hold a
promotion symposium this year to market the minerals discovered in
commercial quantities in the country over the past years.
</P>
<P>
Sanaa press Friday quoted him as saying that resources of
marble, granite, semi precious stones and raw material for cement
industry were discovered in Yemen in the past years.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLA -- The German trading and industrial mission in
Palestine said Germany's aid to the Palestinian National Authority
amounted to about 70 million U.S. dollars last year, Al Hayat
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The director of the mission Abdul Hadi Abu Sharkh said at a
recently held workshop that Germany is engaged in the
Palestinians' projects, such as waste water treatment,
infrastructural and industrial development.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The United States has expressed interest in
participating in Lebanon's power and energy projects despite the
competition from Europe, An Nahar newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. interest was conveyed by U.S. Ambassador in Beirut
David Satterfield during recent talks with Lebanese officials.
</P>
<P>
He laid emphasis on three projects in which his country wishes
to be involved.
</P>
<P>
These include a project to transport natural gas from the
Syrian town of Homs to Lebanon's southern refinery of Zahrani, a
project to transport liquid gas via a pumping station in the
northern town of Batroun and a project to control the electricity
supply by a remote control mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
