<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Involve in Balkan Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
here Friday that his country is "making a commitment to take
generous, immediate, and unilateral steps to improve market access
for products made in southeast Europe".
</P>
<P>
"I will work with the United States Congress to establish a
trade preference program similar to our Andean initiative, which
will offer duty-free treatment for most of the region's exports,"
he told world leaders here attending the so-called Stability Pact
Summit through a written statement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said nations in the region should be brought into the
World Trade Organization on commercially acceptable terms, and be
provided the technical assistance they need to meet those terms.
</P>
<P>
He also called for promoting private investment in the region's
economies, and supporting the development of the region's private
sector. "To that end, America's Overseas Private Investment
Corporation will establish a 150-million-US-dollar investment fund
for the region and a 200-million-US-dollar credit line," he said.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (EBRD), the United States will set up a trust fund
designed to help businesses in the southeast Europe become more
competitive and viable, said Clinton. But he said his
administration would first consult with the Congress.
</P>
<P>
"We would be willing to contribute 15 million dollars in the
first year, and to consider up to 50 million dollars overall, as
long as the EBRD targets an additional 80 million dollars for the
region," he detailed the American plan.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we will support the creation of a regional equity
fund of up to 300 million dollars, with financing from the
international financial institutions, to make equity investments
in private enterprises in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president also indicated the incoming action by his
administration. "Our Commerce Secretary William Daley will also
sponsor a mission to the region to showcase trade and investment
opportunities and build new business partnerships," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here hold that the United States is ready to deeply
involve in the economic reconstruction process in Balkan region
through various action plans which were modeled as western powers'
anti-Communism Mashall Plan for rebuilding Europe after the second
World War.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from major western countries and Balkan nations and
heads of main international organizations ended the Stability Pact
Summit this afternoon after issuing a Declaration calling for
integration of Balkans into a single European model. The Stability
Pact, which was initiated and already adopted by the European
Union, has been widely regarded as a new Mashall Plan to promote
western ideology, value and way of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
