<HEADLINE> S. Africa Military to Set up Peace-keeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
Defense Force (SANDF) will set up a unit of military observers to
be deployed during peace-keeping missions, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The observers could be deployed in United Nations, Organization
of African Unity (OAU), and Southern African Development Community
(SADC) peace missions, SAPA quoted an internal bulletin of the
defense force as saying.
</P>
<P>
A decision to this effect was made at a Defense Staff Council
meeting last week, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
The unit would comprise two pools, with the first comprising
liaison officers acting as advance parties for possible
deployments. The second group would be made up of trained U.N.
military observers.
</P>
<P>
The defense force said majors, lieutenant-colonels, captains
and colonels would be considered for the job.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers should be proficient in English and be willing to be
deployed for periods ranging from six months to a year.
</P>
<P>
Applications opened Tuesday and training would start on August
23, the bulletin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
