<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Reiterates "One China" Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Zimbabwe said in a statement
that Zimbabwe deplored any statements or actions which undermined
or threatened the sovereignty of China and that nation's path to
reunification.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe believes that any such action can only lead to
instability and possibly even to open conflict," the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was reacting to remarks made by Taiwanese leader
Lee Teng-hui in which he defined the relationship between Taiwan
and mainland China as "state to state or at least special state to
state relations".
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Zimbabwe's Deputy Foreign Minister Nicolas
Goche told Xinhua that Zimbabwe's policy on one China has never
changed. "We recognize only one China, that's the People's
Republic of China. Taiwan has always been a part of China, it can
never be recognized as a state, it can only be recognized as a
province of the People's Republic of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
