<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Stock Exchange To Become Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The London Stock Exchange (LSE) is
planning to scrap its status as a Mutual organization and become a
private company.
</P>
<P>
The LSE announced Friday that it would not initially sell
shares to the public, but the new structure would allow for
increased investment by dealers and others.
</P>
<P>
The organization, which has been a Mutual for 200 years will
stop short of floating shares in itself but will be privately
owned by its 294 member firms.
</P>
<P>
The plans follow a series of announcements by overseas stock
exchanges including the New York stock exchange and America's
Nasdaq market to turn themselves into shareholder-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The new structure was unanimously approved at a meeting of the
14 member board on Thursday. It is subject to approval by a vote
of the full membership of 294 shareholders, according to the
announcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
