<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Registers Trade Surplus in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The 11-nation euro zone has
registered a trade surplus with the rest of the world in May this
year, Eurostat reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau of the European community said that the
euro zone chalked up a trade surplus of 2.7 billion euro (2.8
billion U.S. dollars) compared with 5.4 billion euro (5.67 billion
U.S. dollars) in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The same month a year ago saw a trade surplus of 8.7 billion
euro (9.1 billion dollars) for the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The European statistical bureau also reported that the
15-nation European Union had registered a trade deficit of 1.4
billion euro (1.47 billion dollars) with the rest of the world in
May this year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the European Union posted a 3.3-billion-euro
trade surplus with the rest of the world in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The EU trade growth with most of its major trade partners was
weak or falling in the first four months of the year. EU exports
to China and Hungary were the exceptions. Exports to China and
Hungary both grew by 16 percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
The biggest drop in exports was registered in Russia where EU
exports decreased by 55 percent. The next sharpest drop was in
Norway at 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Envoy to Head U.N. Security Council in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Martin Andjaba, Namibian
ambassador to the United Nations, will succeed Hasmy Agam of
Malaysia as the president of the U.N. Security Council as of
August 1.
</P>
<P>
Hasmy, the permanent representative to the United Nations, took
up the position on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council has primary
responsibility for the maintenance of international peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation body has 5 permanent members and 10 members,
elected by the General Assembly for two-year terms.
</P>
<P>
The 15 Council members rotate the presidency every month
according to the alphabetical order of the country names.
</P>
</TEXT>
