<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Reiterate Rejection of Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official on
Friday reiterated the Palestinians' rejection of a proposal made
by the Israeli prime minister on the implementation of the Wye
interim peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon arrival in Cairo, Palestinian
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath
said the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) would not accept
Ehud Barak's idea on delaying troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Shaath stressed that the PNA has also turned down Barak's
proposal to combine part of the last October's Wye accord with the
negotiations for a final peace deal between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Since his election in May, Barak has repeatedly expressed
readiness to push the peace talks with the Palestinians forward.
He also said he would carry out the Wye peace agreement, which
calls on Israel to hand over another 13.1 percent of the West Bank
to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But in the meantime, he proposed to blend the third and last
phase of pullback with the final status talks after implementing
the second phase.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has rejected the proposal,
insisting that Israel implement the Wye accord "fully and
accurately" before the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Shaath expressed satisfaction with Barak's pledges to advance
the talks with the Palestinians but was critical of him for lack
of deeds to follow his words.
</P>
<P>
"Barak's words are satisfactory but his lack of deeds do not
give us confidence," the Palestinian minister said.
</P>
<P>
Shaath came here to accompany Arafat in a meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on Saturday to discuss the latest
developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
