<HEADLINE> Rwandan, Ugandan Presidents Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu left the country's capital Kigali Friday morning for a
meeting with his Ugandan counterpart Yoweri Museveni, Rwanda News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
''The present visit is in the framework of regular
consultations between the leaders of both countries on matters of
mutual interests," the news agency quoted a source from the office
of President Bizimungu as saying.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Mazimhaka, the Minister in President's Office, and
Colonel Frank Mugambage, deputy chief of staff of Rwandan army,
are with the president during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Discussions are said to have taken place at Kisozi, 40 km
outside Kampala, at Museveni's private residence.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan president returned in Kigali late Friday afternoon,
but refused to talk to reporters who were curious to know what the
prompt visit to Uganda was about.
</P>
<P>
Unnamed sources in Kigali said the visit was aimed at levelling
 differences between the two countries relating to the split in
the main rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD)
which has blocked the implementation of the Lusaka peace accord.
</P>
