<HEADLINE> COMESA to Improve Communication, Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Member states of Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) have been urged to make
efforts in improving regional communication, navigation and air
traffic management system toward the establishment of a free trade
area on October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the first meeting of aeronautical experts
and directors of civil aviation in Lusaka Friday, COMESA Acting
Secretary General Sindiso Ngwenya said the liberalization of the
COMESA air transport market is part of the on-going COMESA program
on liberalizing trade in goods and services hence a full
liberalization of the COMESA transport market will coincide with
the launching of the COMESA Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
He said the council of ministers, at its 7th meeting held in
Nairobi, Kenya, in May 1999, approved the system and regulations
for implementing the first phase of the liberalization of air
transport market for air cargo and scheduled passenger services
within COMESA.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the management system will improve safety
of aircraft when flying over the regional air space, he said,
adding that feasibility study had definitively concluded that the
implementation of the system is not only technically feasible but
financially viable.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the meeting, Zambian Deputy Minister of
Communications and Transport Mann Muyuni called for full
liberalization of the airline industry as the COMESA moves toward
a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
He said the airline sub-sector is one of the most important
industries in the facilitation of the achievement of economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
"We need to undertake various policy and institutional reforms
so that the region regulatory authorities and airport services
providers are ready to serve the airline industry in the most
efficient manner," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
