<HEADLINE> Sao Tome Trade Union Threatens to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- State Trade Union (STU) of Sao Tome
and Principe has threatened to paralyse governmental organs if the
authorities refuse to increase their minimum salary by 2,150
percent, according to a report reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of STU Aurelio Silva said after a meeting
with leaders of other two important trade union organizations that
the proposal of augmenting salary will be delivered to the
government next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Trade Union asked the government to increase the minimum
salary of public officers to 900,000 dobras (about 300 U.S.
dollars) from the current 40,000 dobras (13 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We will paralyse the country," said Silva, "if the government
doesn't accept our proposal."
</P>
<P>
Silva made it clear that the Union will give the government 15
days to prepare for the negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The largest agricultural and stock farming company of the
country, Company Santa Margarida, carried out an open-ended strike
last month, with an aim to increase their wages from 11 U.S.
dollars to 50 dollars. The strike is still going on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
