<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Detain 96 Rioters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian police held 96
rioters Friday for staging an illegal demonstration in the capital
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The riots happened at areas close to two mosques in the
Kariakoo area in the capital. Two rioters were injured and have
been hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Rioters threw stones at people, wounding several policemen and
many civilians in the streets. They have also damaged automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Of the detained, 74 were men and 22 women, Regional Police
Commander Alfred Gewe said, adding that they are being questioned.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said Moslems started gathering at the Manyema Mosque
at Ukame/ Mafia street junction around 1:30 p.m. soon after
mid-day Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
They said members of the mosque moved out peacefully after
prayers, but within a few minutes, large crowd of people from all
directions assembled at the mosque.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Moslems have warned to gather and demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
Finding that the situation was unusual, patrol police arrived
at the mosque and ordered hundreds of people gathering there to
leave.
</P>
<P>
People there did not retreat, instead they moved toward the
patrol policemen, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
"Few minutes later a contingent of armed Field Force Unit, the
anti-riot force, came with other policemen in a convoy of about
eight vehicles to disperse the crowd," a witness said.
</P>
<P>
"But the irate people started raining stones randomly," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said shops were being closed and everybody on the
street started running for safety. Many people got injured while
properties were damaged.
</P>
<P>
As the police and security forces attempted to surround the
mosque, two people inside tried to escape and jumped down from the
mosque fence, but sustained multiple wounds. The two have been
sent to the Muhimbili Medical Center for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said unrest also took place at another Mosque in the
Kariakoo area.
</P>
<P>
The regional police commander said that a police officer,
Pakilo Mwaitebels, was stoned and wounded on the left arm with his
wrist watch dismantled during scuffles with rioters.
</P>
<P>
Gewe said those who have been seized will be taken to court
facing charges of wounding people, damaging property and causing
social unrest.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tanzanian Minister of Education and Culture Juma
Kapuya promised that Moslem girl students in schools will be
allowed to hijab, or wear head scarf, during Friday, the prayer
day.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya, however, later changed his position amid concerns of a
group of members of parliament, who said Tanzania is a secular
country in which students are supposed to wear school uniforms
when attending classes.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya's change of position has caused wide protests from
Moslems, who threatened to stage demonstrations this week.
</P>
<P>
However, Tanzanian government leaders have warned them not to
stage illegal demonstrations, otherwise they will face punishment.
</P>
<P>
About one third of the Tanzanian population are Moslems, one
third are Christians while the rest hold indigenous beliefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDCP Uses Satellite Remote Sensing to Detect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
International Drug Council Program (UNDCP) Friday announced that
it has designated a plan to use remote sensing (RS) and other
space-related technologies to monitor the illicit cultivation of
narcotic crops, particularly the opium poppy and the coco bush
which feed the international drug trade.
</P>
<P>
Initial findings of a joint project, conducted by UNDCP and the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization in 1993 and 1994,
established that it was possible to monitor the growth of illicit
crops with the aid of RS technologies.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, satellite-based platforms have been developed
and launched which, combined with new innovative image processing
technologies, provide the opportunity to produce accurate high
resolution images enabling the identification of illicit crops at
an economically viable cost.
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations General Assembly Special Session on the
World Drug Problem in June 1998, Member States decided to work
closely with UNDCP to create strategies to eliminate or
significantly reduce illicit cultivation of the opium poppy,
cannabis and coco bush by the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
The Member States requested the UNDCP to intensify the
collection and analysis of previously incomplete data the extent
of these crops, to aid their elimination strategy and measure its
progress.
</P>
<P>
Taking up the challenge, UNDCP developed a program to establish
an International Network for the Monitoring of Narcotic Crops by
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The objective is to enable countries affected by illicit
cultivation to assess growth levels of narcotic crops and
determine trends at a national level.
</P>
<P>
During the now completed first phase of this program, UNDCP
reached an agreement with the European Space Agency to place
satellite imagery technology at the disposal of governments for the
purpose of monitoring illicit crops.
</P>
<P>
Some economies of scale were achieved, thus minimizing the cost
of developing RS technology for user countries, UNDCP said. The
provision of technical assistance tailored to the individual needs
of governments is envisaged in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The International Network for the Monitoring of Narcotic
Crops will also validate the methods of monitoring the
cultivation of coca and opium plants with satellite-procured
imagery. It will formulate guidelines for their use in addition
to identifying ways of controlling the quality of the data
obtained.
</P>
<P>
Following this study, governments should be better able to
assess the feasibility, modalities, needs and not lease of all,
the financial requirements for using satellite remote sensing
technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
