<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Gives Message to Sarajevo Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Friday that the Stability Pact Summit being
held here marks a new beginning in the efforts of the
international community to end the Balkan wars of this century.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief delivered the message through Carl Bildt, his
special Balkan envoy. "After a decade of conflict that has taken
us from Croatia and Bosnia to Kosovo, we have now returned to
Sarajevo with a strong determination to achieve lasting peace," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"With this meeting, and with the extraordinary attention and
dedication devoted to overcoming the devastating results of the
last of the Balkan wars," Annan said, "the international community
has the opportunity to honor its pledges towards this region, and
thereby enable the peoples of the region to achieve stability in
their own lives."
</P>
<P>
He said the Sarajevo meeting will give all efforts of the
United Nations "new inspiration and new initiative" so that "we
enter the new century with renewed faith in lasting peace and
prosperity for the entire region".
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit, attended by leaders from more than 30
countries, ended here Friday afternoon with a declaration calling
for the integration of the Balkans into a single European model.
</P>
<P>
After the summit, U.S. President Bill Clinton gave a speech to
a group of representatives from certain countries and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact, initiated and adopted by the European Union,
was agreed in principle at the summit.
</P>
<P>
In the Sarajevo Declaration, the leaders expressed their
support for the appointment of Bodo Hombach as the special
coordinator of the Stability Pact by the EU Council, as endorsed
by the OSCE (Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe).
</P>
<P>
"We pledge our full cooperation to the Special Coordinator in
the achievement of our objectives," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
