<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Death Toll in Heat Wave Reaches 77 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The heat wave hitting the
Midwest and the East in the United States has led to the deaths of
at least 77 people since July 19, government officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Missouri State has the highest death toll at 27, followed by
Illinois and Ohio with 19 and 10 deaths respectively.
</P>
<P>
This summer's unrelenting heat has been sapping energy from
outdoor workers, drying up crops and turning forests into kindling
across Connecticut State and elsewhere in the nation, according to
the officials.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures were over 35 degrees centigrade from the Plains to
the East coast in the country.
</P>
<P>
To the north, the weather was even worse. It was 44 degrees
centigrade in Pierre, South Dakota State, topping the record of
42.8 degrees centigrade set in 1933. The temperature was a
record-tying 40 degrees centigrade in Bismarck, North Dakota
State, and an all-time high of 39.4 degrees centigrade in
Dickinson, North Dakota State.
</P>
<P>
The heat was expected to last at least until Friday before a
change in the jet stream brings cooler air from Canada to northern
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New-Home Sales Rebound in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Friday that sales of new single-family homes rebounded in June,
rising 3.1 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 929,000
units, better than expected.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expected new homes sales to increase as buyers
scramble to lock in the best deals to beat slowly advancing
mortgage rates. That was the reason existing-home sales hit a
record high in June.
</P>
<P>
This week, the average interest rate on a 30-year fixed rate
mortgage was 7.70 percent, up from 7.52 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
New-home sales fell 4.1 percent to 901,000 units in May.
</P>
<P>
June's increase in sales pushed prices up as well. The median
price for a new home, meaning half of all homes sold in June for
less and half for more, jumped 4.7 percent to 157,000 dollars, up
from May's median price of 149,900 dollars. June's price was the
highest since February's record of 159,900 dollars.
</P>
<P>
In today's personal income and spending report, the Commerce
Department said that wages rose 0.5 percent in June, while farm
proprietors' income, which fell sharply in May, increased
dramatically, mainly reflecting federal subsidy payments to
farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
