<HEADLINE> India Defends Credit Line to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- India said on friday that the
credit line it provided to Iraq earlier this week was within the
framework of relevant U.N. resolutions on sanctions and subject to
prior approval of the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry told the press
here that "this line of credit is no different from similar
agreements signed by several other countries with Iraq."
</P>
<P>
India agreed to provided Iraq with a credit line of 25 million
U.S. dollars for supply of humanitarian goods during a visit this
week by Petroleum and Natural Gas Minister V. K. Ramamurthy.
</P>
<P>
Foreign press quoted Ranamurthy as saying in Baghdad Thursday
that he was aware that the grant would violate U.N. sanctions but
his country would never allow a friend like Iraq to suffer.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman claimed friday that Ramamurthy, who was in
Baghdad for the second meeting of the Indo-Iraqi Joint Commission,
was "misquoted."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Ramamurthy actually reiterated that
India adheres to U.N. resolutions on Iraq and its cooperation with
Baghadad would be in accordance with these resolutions.
</P>
<P>
India has traditionally had good relations with Iraq based on
long-standing people-to-people contacts, the spokesman said,
adding that "while we remain concerned at the suffering of the
Iraqi people, we strictly adhere to all relevant U.N. resolutions
regarding Iraq."
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said that Washington was "seeking
confirmation or clarification from the government of India about
exactly what he (Ramamurthy) has agreed to" in extending the
credit line.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources here said that the credit line was to help
Iraq buy goods including 100,000 tons of wheat besides medical
equipment and tea from India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
