<HEADLINE> India Firm on Position on Talks with Pakistan: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- India Friday stuck to its
position on Pakistan's renewed offer for dialogue, asserting that
it would consider resumption of talks only after Islamabad
reaffirmed the sanctity and inviolability of the line of control
(LOC) and took tangible steps to stop cross-border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We consider cross-border terrorism to be a violation of the
LOC and Pakistan must take tangible steps to stop it and to
dismantle the apparatus of terrorists located in Pakistan and
territories under their control," a spokesman of the External
Affairs Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistan foreign office spokesman reportedly said in
Islamabad Friday that "India needs to commit itself to a dialogue
which should lead to the final settlement of the Kashmir issue."
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman said that New Delhi had clarified more
than once that India had been the initiator of the dialogue
process which was based on the Simla Agreement signed in early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
He said that the dialogue process with Islamabad was
interrupted by "Pakistan's intrusion and aggression and occupation
of the territory on the Indian side of the LOC," the de facto
border between the two neighbors. 
</P>
