<HEADLINE> Egypt, EU to Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is to discuss with the
European Union (EU) the role the European bloc can play in helping
reactivate the Middle East peace process, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will meet with Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen to discuss
the issue during her upcoming visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Halonen, whose country is holding EU's rotating presidency for
the second half of 1999, is expected to arrive in Egypt Sunday on
the first leg of her regional tour, which will also take her to
Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European organization wants to play a key role in
the Arab-Israeli peace talks and keeps close coordination on the
issue with Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty
with Israel and an active mediator in the peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he would hold talks with his Finnish counterpart on
the latest developments in the peace drive and means of promoting
the European role in helping advance the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Since his elections in May, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has repeatedly expressed readiness to push the peace talks with
the Palestinians forward and resume negotiations with Syria, which
came to halt in early 1996. Barak has also voiced welcome to any
efforts aimed at giving momentum to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he would also discuss with Halonen ways of boosting
the Egyptian-EU partnership within the framework of the Barcelona
process.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona process, or Euro-Med partnership, kicked off
during the 1995 conference in Barcelona, Spain, is aimed at
forging close cooperation in political coordination, economy,
trade, security and social affairs among the EU members and 12
Mediterranean countries, including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and the EU have endorsed the text of their
partnership agreement after nearly four years of negotiations. The
accord provides for more open trade, coordination in many economic
and financial areas, a political dialog and joint efforts to
combat money laundering and terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
