<HEADLINE> UK Economic Recovery Gathers Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The UK economy is growing more
quickly than forecast, pushing away any fears of recession and
showing the economy recovering.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) estimated Friday that
the total output for the second quarter was up 1.2 percent
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures came hard on the heels of revised data on Thursday,
which showed creeping growth of 0.1 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the British economy has now grown in every quarter
since the end of a deep recession in early 1992.
</P>
<P>
A Treasury spokesman said, "These preliminary growth figures
are encouraging, in line with the Budget forecast and show that
the UK is steering a course of stability."
</P>
<P>
City analysts now believe the economy is likely to meet
Chancellor Gordon Brown's 1999 growth forecast of between 1
percent and 1.5 percent, a figure previously thought to be
over-optimistic.
</P>
<P>
It is now commonly believed here that the UK economy is on
course for Chancellor's "soft landing". 
</P>
</TEXT>
