<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Iraqis Killed in U.S., British Air-strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were killed and 23
others were wounded Friday when U.S. and British warplanes
attacked several sites in northern and southern Iraq, the Iraqi
armed forces said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the statement as saying that 11
formations of enemy planes made 24 sorties over the provinces of
Dohuk, Irbil and Mosul, bombing civilian facilities, killing six
people and wounding 21 others.
</P>
<P>
The allied planes also attacked a number of civilian targets in
the southern province of Najaf, 160 kilometers south of Baghdad,
killing three people and injuring two others, the INA reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Iraqi air defense units fought back and
forced the enemy planes to flee back to their bases in Turkey,
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time in two weeks that Iraq has reported
fatalities in the airstrikes by allied planes patrolling the
no-fly zones in northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen civilian were killed on July 18 and eight were killed
on Thursday in the regular U.S.-British warplane attacks on Iraqi
civilian and military targets.
</P>
<P>
The United States-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones
in Iraq in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from any possible attacks by the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British airstrikes, Iraq has
declared that it does not recognize the restricted zones because
they were imposed unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain without
the authorization of the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
