<HEADLINE> U.S. Planes Attack Iraqi Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes conducted
repeated strikes on Iraqi targets in both southern and northern
no-fly zones on Friday, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon released two statements from U.S. Southern Command
in Tampa, Florida, which oversees operations in the southern
no-fly zones in Iraq, and from the European Command in Germany,
responsible for operations over the northern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The statement from the Southern Command said the attack in
the south involved U.S. Air Force F-16 and Navy F/A-18 Hornets
and F-14 Tomcats as well as British GR-1 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
And the European Command said that U.S. Air Force F-15s and
F-16s dropped laser-guided bombs on anti-aircraft sites in the
northern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said after the bombing that nine people were killed and
23 injured in the U.S. air raids.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman as saying
six people were killed and 21 injured in the north while three
died and two were injured in the south.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones in both southern and norther Iraq were
imposed by the United States and Britain right after the Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad would not recognize the imposition of the no-fly
zones and repeated its warning that it would shoot any Western
warplanes invading its sovereign air space. 
</P>
