<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urges End to Fighting in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba called Friday for an end to the continued fighting in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
When meeting with visiting Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
here, he said that nobody has the reason to continue fighting
because all the parties including the rebels have agreed with the
cease-fire agreement signed on July 10 by the warring countries
involved in the 11-month war in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from Congo, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola inked the
pact, so did the presidents from Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi in
Lusaka of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who mediated the cease-fire agreement, said that
Zambia and Tanzania are making efforts to see the agreement also
signed by the rebels fighting to topple Congolese President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the time is up to end the conflict."
</P>
<P>
The rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (CRD) and the Movement
for the Liberation for Congo (MLC) did not sign the agreement
because of the disagreement over who would sign on behalf of the
CRD.
</P>
<P>
The CRD split into two factions in May this year, with Ernest
Wamba Dia Wamba who founded the organization being kicked out by
the faction led by Emile Illunga.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, Chiluba said that the two countries
have a lot to do to increase their trade and called for
strengthened relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
On the protracted war in Angola he called for political
willingness from the waring sides to settle the differences
peacefully. Civil war renewed since last December between the
Angolan government and the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the region does not want to be engulfed by
conflicts but wishes to enjoy a good quality of life and
development.
</P>
<P>
In reply to Chiluba, Mkapa praised the Zambian President for
his efforts in securing the peace agreement to end the war in
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
