<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Concerns Over Law and Order in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A top U.N. official Friday
said "the major concern at present remains law and order" in
Kosovo and the world body is no longer tolerating the terrorist
acts in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. undersecretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, told a press conference here that it is
intolerable to see that mainly Serbs and some Albanians were
killed after the return of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA)
in June.
</P>
<P>
"When I left (Kosovo) just over a week ago, every day four to
six inhabitants of Kosovo were being killed," he said. "In recent
weeks, usually Serbs and Roma, but also Albanians, particularly
those who have been accused of collaborating with the former
authorities" in the province.
</P>
<P>
"And often the killings were carried out in a manner that would
contribute to creating a crime of terror," he said. "This is
clearly not something that we can tolerate."
</P>
<P>
De Mello headed the U.N. Interim Administration Mission in
Kosovo before Bernard Kouchner of France took up the post.
</P>
<P>
The top U.N. official also rejected U.S. charges that the U.N.
had contributed to lawlessness in Kosovo by failing to recruit
police quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
"We are deploying an international police force throughout
Kosovo," he said. "I wish the United Nations had battalions of
civilian administrators and civilian policemen on standby in
Macedonia" as the international peacekeepers did.
</P>
<P>
"But we don't," he said.
</P>
<P>
"After all, the purpose of the U.N. deployment in Kosovo is to
promote self-governance, is to promote autonomy to the extent that
these persons, particularly at the municipal level, are doing a
decent job both in terms of their competence, but also in terms of
their inclusive, democratic and multi-ethnic approach to their
jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have also, as you know, established the Kosovo Transition
Council not without difficulty," and the Transitional Council is
currently "the supreme administrative body in Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Mello and Kouchner, the U.N. special representative for
Kosovo, chaired the first meeting of the Council two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission also started the recruitment of local police
force, and 20,000 application forms have been distributed
throughout Yugoslavia, he said. "Eight thousand applications have
been received the day before yesterday."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. task of recruiting, financing and deploying 3,100
policemen in Kosovo has proven difficult with some 41 countries
volunteering police officers but not sending them immediately.
These include the United States, which has offered a list of 100
names and added 200 more after the criticism of U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The deputy U.N. spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a
press conference Friday that the United Nations now has over 350
civilian policemen in Kosovo and some additional 240 from Canada,
Russia and the United Nations are expected to be on the ground
early this coming week.
</P>
<P>
Under Security Council resolution 1244, adopted on June 10, the
U.N. mission entered Kosovo on June 15.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the mission and structure is "the first
truly integrated of this kind in the history of the Organization,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations provided an umbrella to U.N. agencies and
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which is
the pillar for institution building in the Yugoslav province, and
the European Union and the European Commission, which is in charge
of the post-war reconstruction in the Balkan country, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes Tax Cut Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate voted 57-43 Friday
to push through a 10-year and 792 billion dollar tax cut bill
which President Bill Clinton has vowed to veto.
</P>
<P>
The Senate plan would reduce the 15 percent tax bracket to 14
percent, ease the so-called marriage penalty, reduce estate taxes
and increase contribution limits for Individual Retirement
Accounts.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives also passed a similar tax cut bill
of 792 billion dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton has repeatedly said he would veto any measure
that closely resembles the Senate bill or a similar House measure
because the tax cuts are too large to leave money for Social
Security and other domestic programs and it will endanger the
nation's economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, both Republicans, met with their top deputies to discuss
the timetable for negotiations to resolve differences between the
two bills of the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
"We want to cut taxes and the president wants to spend it.
That's what the fighting is all about," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
Lott said the goal was to get the bill through the House and
Senate by the end of next week, although it will probably be
September, after the congressional August recess, before it is
presented to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reminded Congress again Thursday that the bill faced a
certain veto. In remarks before leaving for Europe, he said the
"large and risky tax cut" could carry America back "to the dark
old days of huge deficits."
</P>
<P>
Clinton has said he would accept no tax cut greater than 300
billion dollars and only if it came after the future of Social
Security and Medicare was secured.
</P>
<P>
Economists have forecast that the budget surplus would total
nearly 3 trillion dollars over the next decade, but the fight was
over what to do with the non-Social Security surplus of
approximately 1 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most Republicans said the bulk of that should be returned to
taxpayers while Democrats insisted that they should be used for
debt reduction and needed spending programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
