<HEADLINE> Europe Markets Recover Despite Week Start On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets ignored new
U.S. inflation fear Friday to make modest advances despite an
uncertain start on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Profit taking and a strong showing in the bank and oil sectors
helped to sustain London blue-chip gains for the entire session on
the day.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark FTSE 100 closed up 114.4 points, a gain of 1.87
percent, at 6,231.9 on provisional volume of 950m shares.
</P>
<P>
The index was lifted a strong performance from the banking
sector, prompted by strong results from Lloyds TSB. First-half
pre-tax profit at Britain's largest retail bank climbed 16 percent
to 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
There was a knock-on effect for other financial stocks with
NatWest Bank rising 46p, or 4 percent, to 1,219p, Barclays up 1.1
percent to 1,823p and HSBC Holdings up 28p to 738p.
</P>
<P>
A strong crude oil market in the U.S. and rising Brent crude
oil prices pushed index heavyweight Shell 26p higher to 503p.
</P>
<P>
Leading shares in Germany rose on the day as talk of a merger
between Viag and Veba helped overcome an extension of Thursday's
fall at DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax overcame a volatile morning session to rise
gently through the day and close up 49.55 points at 5,101.87.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 moved ahead on moves in a narrow group of
stocks, and closed up 75.66 points at 4,382.06, a gain of 1.76
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
