<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM Ends Mile-Stone Visit to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine ended on Friday a two-day mile-stone visit to Algeria,
which marked the returning to normal relations by France and
Algeria after years of troubles.
</P>
<P>
The visit could also be a prelude to a state visit by President
Jacques Chirac to Algeria widely expected later this year.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine had on Friday a five-hour meeting with Algerian
President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who assumed presidency in
mid-April.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that France has a very strong
political will to ``recast'' its relations with Algeria, after
Bouteflika made some declarations and gestures aimed at improving
relations with Western countries while seeking a national
reconciliation at home.
</P>
<P>
He announced that France would re-open two consulates in the
Algerian port city of Oran and the eastern city of Annaba on an
unspecified date in near future.
</P>
<P>
The two consulates were closed in 1994 by France in fear of
terrorist attacks by Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also said that the French national air company Air
France is expected to resume its flights to Algiers soon.
</P>
<P>
``The French government wishes that we can resume the flights
as quickly as possible. The decision of last resort depends on the
president of the air company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Air France suspended its flights to Algeria after an Airbus
passenger plane of the company was hijacked by Islamic militants
at the airport of Algiers in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
A resumption of flights by Air France will mean a recognition
by France of the improvement of security situation in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also said that France will open a cultural center in
Algiers at the beginning of 2000, which will be opened to Algerian
college students and scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
