<HEADLINE> Canada Offers Ethiopia $2m Food Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government will
offer Ethiopia two million U.S. dollars to buy over 9,500 tons of
emergency relief food after it signed a pact with the Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission (DPPC) of Ethiopia here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
DPPC Commissioner Simon Mechale and Canadian ambassador to
Ethiopia John Schram signed the agreement respectively.
</P>
<P>
The relief assistance would bolster the country's national food
reserve, a DPPC press statement said.
</P>
<P>
The relief assistance will substitute the food aid dispatched
by Canada to Ethiopia last year but had been blocked at the Assab
port following the border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea in
May last year, according to the press statement. 
</P>
