<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Okays Renewal of Military Mission in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday voted unanimously to extend the mandate of the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) for a further period of
six months until January 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted on the mandate extension, the Security
Council "reiterates its strong support for the territorial
integrity, sovereignty and political independence of Lebanon
within its internationally recognized boundaries."
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called upon all parties concerned to
cooperate fully with the U.N. force "for the full implementation
of its mandate."
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the Security Council "condemns all
acts of violence committed in particular against the Force, and
urges the parties to put an end to them."
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement, issued at the same time, said the
Security Council "expresses its concern over the continuing
violence in southern Lebanon, regrets of loss of civilian life,
and urges all parties to exercise restraint."
</P>
<P>
"The Council notes with deep concern the high level of
casualties which UNIFIL has suffered and pays a special tribute to
all those who gave their lief while serving in UNIFIL," the
presidential statement said.
</P>
<P>
In his July 21 report to the Security Council, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said, "During the past six months,
the situation in the area remained volatile and continued to give
cause for serious concern."
</P>
<P>
As of June 1999. UNIFIL comprised 4,495 troops, they were from
Fiji, Finland, France, Ghana, India, Ireland, Italy, Nepal and
Poland.
</P>
<P>
"Since the establishment of UNIFIL, 227 members of the Force
have lost their lives," Annan said, "A total of 338 were wounded
by firing, or by mine or bomb explosion."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
