<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Light Plane With 16 People Hijacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A commercial light plane of the
Venezolana Avior airline has been kidnapped by drug traffickers or
Colombian guerrillas, local sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft with 16 passengers aboard disappeared Friday
morning when it was about to land 20 miles from the Guasdalito
airport, about 650 kilometers southwest of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ignacio Arcaya said the aircraft, YV 466
Charli, Beechcraft 1900D, with seats for 19 people, took off
Friday morning from the Simon Bolivar Airport in Maiquetia, and
made a stop in the state of Barinas, from which it continued its
flight to Guasdalito.
</P>
<P>
The two-motor plane, piloted by Capt. Hector Hernandez, lost
contact with the control tower at 09:45 local time.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the plane disappearance is not known, but
according to Arcaya, the local authorities have two hypotheses: a
crash or a possible hijacking, either by common criminals, or by
the Colombian guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking version is acquiring credibility, because the
aircraft lost contact in the border areas with Colombia, where
there are guerrilla groups or paramilitary.
</P>
<P>
Air Force and National Guard helicopters are combing the zone
where the Avior light plane disappeared.
</P>
<P>
There is a contradiction about the number of passengers aboard.
The Globovision television network said, quoting Victor Delgado,
Civilian Transit director, that they are 16, including two pilots,
while the RCTV network says that the lost persons are 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
