<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haul of Ivory Seized in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan security officers seized a
haul of elephant tusks Thursday, the largest since ivory trade
was outlawed worldwide 10 years ago, sources of the Kenya Wildlife
Service (KWS) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 45 seized pieces of ivory were Friday displayed at Maralal
Town in northern Kenya where two suspects are being questioned in
connection with the recovery, said wildlife experts.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, some of the tusks on display had
bullet marks.
</P>
<P>
They noted the Maralal town was notorious for wildlife poaching
in the past decade, saying the haul could signal renewed poaching
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
KWS Chairman Charles Njonjo said at his headquarters here that
"security should be improved countrywide and poachers wiped out"
and he also appealed

to the public to assist security officers to track down the
poachers.
</P>
<P>
Kenya supported the world to ban ivory trade 10 years ago
following decimation of its wildlife resources at the hands of
poachers. Its elephant population had dropped to about 19,000 by
then from an estimated 600,000 in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The present population of elephants in the country has
increased to an estimated 28,000, said the KWS officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the KWS acting Director Nehemiah Rotich, the black
market price of a kilogram of ivory is 2,000 shillings (about 30
U.S. dollars) and an average tusk weighs 32 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The officials expressed their fears of renewed poaching
activities since the International Convention on Endangered
Species allowed South Africa, Namibia and Zimbabwe to dispose of
part of their ivory stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
Kenya remains committed to the ban. Its worry is that
legalizing trade would spark poaching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
