<HEADLINE> British Paratroopers Return From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The first British paratroops to
enter Kosovo as part of the peacekeeping force after the end of
conflict Saturday landed back on British soil.
</P>
<P>
The first flight, carrying about 100 soldiers from Britain's
First Battalion of the Parachute Regiment, touched down at RAF
Brize Norton, Oxfordshire at about noon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They were among 800 British paratroopers who spearheaded NATO's
move into Kosovo after peace terms were agreed.
</P>
<P>
The paratroopers had been flown in by helicopter from Macedonia
and made routes safe for other soldiers before moving to Pristina,
the provincial capital of Kosovo, where they spent six weeks
operating as part of the international peacekeeping force KFOR.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that over the weekend, about 750 British
soldiers from First Parachute and their accompanying forces will
be flown back to the Oxfordshire base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
