<HEADLINE> Eco-Internet Wins Final Stage, Halti Remains Overall Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALI, China, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Team Eco-Internet slashed the
waters of Lake Er-Hai in a traditional Chinese paddle boat to win
the day's final stage in the Mild Seven Outdoor Quest here on
Saturday but Team Halti of Finland still led the field of 24 teams.
</P>
<P>
After the day's six hours and 120 kilometers of racing, Halti
accumlated a total of 15 hours 25 minutes and 26 seconds. Eco-
Internet was second in 15:25:43 and Team Venture Four third in 15:
40:31.
</P>
<P>
Both Halti and Eco-Internet were already throwing down the
gauntlet for the fourth and final day's competition.
</P>
<P>
"Tomorrow will be important and we should do as well as we did
today." said Petri Prosman of Halti.
</P>
<P>
Robert Nagle of Team Eco-Internet was no less bold. "Tomorrow'
s course suits us. It's going to be exciting."
</P>
<P>
Team Beaver Creek-Asia Star, which had laboured at the back of
the pack during the first two days of racing, moved all the way
into fourth position overall, just behind team Adventure Four.
</P>
<P>
The Mild Seven Outdoor Quest is an adventure race. Four-person
teams, each having at least one member of the opposite sex,
contest a variety of endurance sports each day of the four-day
comeptition. The team with the lowest elapsed time at the end
will be declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
First prize for this event, which attracts the top triathletes,
adventure racers, mountain bikers, and cross-country skiers in the
world, is 46,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a contest-withing-a-contest, race organizers have added 10,
000 U.S. dollars bonus for the final two days of competition. The
10 teams with lowest combined time for Days Three and Four will
each receive 1,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
