<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ontario Sees Tripling of Hazardous Waste Imports From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Canada's southeastern province of
Ontario is becoming a chemical garbage dump for the U.S.,
according to a local newspaper "Ottawa Citizen" Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hazardous waste imports from the U.S. nearly tripled between
1994 and 1998, from 85,000 tons to 230,000, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Ontario's exports of hazardous waste to the U.S. over the same
period rose by 40 percent to 145,000 tons from 105,000, it added.
</P>
<P>
Local environmentalists attribute the imbalance to lax Ontario
disposal standards in the face of the tightening U.S. standards.
</P>
<P>
But Ontario Environment Minister Tony Clement insists most of
the responsibility lies with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is urging federal Environment
Minister Christine Stewart to investigate ways to curb imports of
hazardous waste, the newspaper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
