<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Explanation Can Cover up Aim of "Two States" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China will not accept the attempt
by Lee Teng-hui to separate Taiwan from China with the statement
of "special state-to-state relations," according to a special
commentary co-written by the "People's Daily" and Xinhua News
Agency here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Daohan, president of the Association for Relations Across
the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) in a speech made on July 12 demanded
that his counterpart, Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the Straits
Exchange Foundation (SEF), clarify remarks made by Li Teng-hui and
himself on redefining the relations of the two sides as "state-to-
state," the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities made no response for 18 days. Yesterday
afternoon, they faxed ARATS a letter and a written speech by Koo
Chen-fu, which not only repeated Lee's "two states" statement but
also added the words "fully reflecting the will of people in
Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The written speech totally violates the "one China" principle
already reached by both sides of the Taiwan Straits in 1992, and
was of course rejected by ARATS, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
An ARATS official said that the written speech, which further
promulgated the "two states" statement, will be strongly opposed
by all people in China and cannot be accepted by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
People have taken note that Koo's written speech canceled out
the first part of Lee Teng-hui's remarks redefining relations
between the two sides as "state-to-state, or at least special
state-to-state relations," and also said such "special
relationship" will lay a basis for equality between both sides of
the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the "special state-to-state relations" statement is a
"two states" statement, the commentary noted.
</P>
<P>
Koo's written speech tried to defend Lee Teng-hui's "special
state-to-state relations" statement by cooking up several
explanations such as "both sides share a similar culture and a
special sentiment." If Lee Teng-hui has a sincere understanding of
these explanations the only conclusion should be the 'one China'
principle rather than "special state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
Now that the "two states" statement has totally destroyed the
basis of bilateral contacts, exchanges, and dialogues between the
two sides of the Taiwan Straits and distorted cross-Straits
relations into "relations between the two countries," isn't it
ridiculous to talk about the reunification of China? the
commentary asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
