<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Seeks World Sanctions if India Refuses Talks on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said Saturday that the
world community must reject India's diversionary tactics and exert
pressure including threat of sanctions if New Delhi continues to
refuse a meaningful dialogue with Pakistan on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz here
at a press conference upon his return from a tour of Helsinki,
Bucharest and London.
</P>
<P>
"If the world is interested in resolving the Kashmir issue, it
must forcefully reject India's diversionary tactics and exert
maximum pressure including threat of international sanctions if
India continues to refuse a meaningful dialogue with Pakistan on
Kashmir," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said India insists that Kashmir is a bilateral issue and
has to be resolved between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
However, at the same time, India sets preconditions for the
resumption of bilateral dialogue, like the complete withdrawal of
"freedom fighters" from India-held Kashmir, the inviolability of
the Line of Control in Kashmir and stopping all abetment of cross
border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Aziz described New Delhi's preconditions for the dialogue as
"totally unrealistic." He queried, "How can a meaningful dialogue
take place in the face of these double standards?"
</P>
<P>
He said that even when passions and tensions were not so high,
dialogue with India in the past 10 years over the Kashmir issue at
different levels proved totally futile.
</P>
<P>
He said during his meetings with European officials, there was
considerable appreciation of Pakistan's view on India's persistent
aversion to any outside involvement in the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said all the European leaders whom he met were deeply
concerned about the dangerous consequence of the non-resolution of
the Kashmir dispute and the continuing differences between
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
"The acquisition of nuclear capability by both countries has
added, in their view, a new and ominous dimension to the
situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz noted that Pakistan has committed to composite dialogue
with India but wants settlement of the Kashmir issue on priority.
</P>
<P>
"The impression (created by India) that the other issues can be
taken first and Kashmir later is no longer feasible because of the
explosive nature of the Kashmir issue," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
"First progress should be made on Kashmir and then on other
issues," the Pakistani foreign minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the eight-point agreement signed by the foreign
secretaries of the two countries in June 1997 and endorsed under
the Lahore Declaration also spelt out issues relating to peace and
security and strategic restraint regime.
</P>
<P>
"These issues can also be taken on priority," said Aziz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
