<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Approaching Opposition's Key Air base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
militia Saturday managed to push forward to within five kilometers
of the opposition's key air base, sources from Kabul said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban forces, after a fierce fighting, approached Bagram of
Parwan province, the location of the only air base under the
control of the anti-Taliban forces led by former defense minister
Ahmad Shah Masood of the Jamiat-i-Islamai group, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who control nearly 90 percent of the war-ravaged
country, launched a major offensive Wednesday in a bid to wipe out
the opposition and extend their strict Islamic rule over the rest
of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been fighting mainly on five battlefields --
the so-called Old Road, the New Road, Koh-i-Safi, the twin
districts of Tagab and Nejrab as well as Ghorband, all north or
northeast of the capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The frontlines ring the southern and western perimeter of the
Panjsher Valley, the last stronghold of the anti-Taliban forces.
</P>
<P>
Masood and his troops, mainly Tajiks and ethnic Hazaras, Uzbeks
and Turkmen, have heavily fortified themselves in the Panjsher
Valley, where they have been fighting five years against the
ethnic Pushtun Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban still hold Nejrab, one of the seven known entries
into the valley, which they seized Wednesday, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of soldiers have reportedly been killed in three-day
battles and more than 1,000 others are estimated to have been
injured.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition forces claimed they repulsed a
Taliban assault in Dar-i-Safi in the northern province of
Samangan, killing 28 of the attackers.
</P>
<P>
Hussain Sohail, a spokesman for the Northern Alliance, said
Saturday that the opposition was ready for peace talks and warned
the Taliban that they could not achieve a military victory.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the Taliban's call Friday for surrender, saying no
unilateral cease-fire is possible.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the two warring parties earlier this month
in Tashkent, Uzbekistan, failed to yield a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
