<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Meet on Israeli Plan for Wye Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat ended talks Saturday that was
said to focus on Israel's plan for a delayed implementation of the
Wye River Accord.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Arafat did not speak to reporters after their
meeting in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria, 220
kilometers northwest of Cairo, which came two days after Mubarak
discussed the Israel's proposal with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak in the same city.
</P>
<P>
Arafat later held talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa at a tourist resort in the west of Alexandria. Neither man
spoke to the press afterwards, and Arafat flew to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye agreement, Israel should pull back from another
13.1 percent of the West Bank. After implementing the first stage
of the three-phase withdrawal, former Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu shelved the accord.
</P>
<P>
Since election in May, Barak has repeated his promise to carry
out the deal. But meanwhile, he proposed to blend the third phase
of pullback with the negotiations for a final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat opposes the plan, saying that he wants Wye to be
implemented as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Later Saturday, Arafat is to chair a meeting of the Central
Committee of Fatah, the party led by him and the main movement in
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being held in Cairo because Israel will not
allow three of the committee's members to enter the Palestinian
self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
