<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Material Evidence of Nanjing Massacre Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The remains of 21 more Chinese
victims of the 1937 Nanjing Massacre were exhumed today in the
Jiangdongmen area of Nanjing in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
With those found last year, there are now five layers of
remains at this site, and we can see what the Japanese invaders
did to the Chinese during the massacre through an examination of
these remains. Some of the victims' heads were cut off, and a 10-
cm-long rusty reinforcing bar was found pierced through the pelvis
of a female victim. Most of the dead were young men.
</P>
<P>
From April to September last year, a total of 50 bodies were
found in the area, and historians confirmed that they were Nanjing
Massacre victims after examinations and medical tests.
</P>
<P>
Qi Kang, an academician at the Chinese Academy of Sciences and
a well-known architectural designer, has designed a hall for the
remains in collaboration with his postgraduate students.
</P>
<P>
The Memorial Hall to the Nanjing Massacre Victims will organize
a group of archeologists to continue excavating the area. The
remains will be preserved as material evidence of the atrocities
committed by the Japanese troops during their invasion of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
