<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Using Scientific Philosophy to Conquer Fatalistic Theory of Falun Gong: Officials and People (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Officials and people from all
walks of life in China today refuted the fatalistic philosophy
propagated by Falun Gong, and vowed their determination to build a
scientific philosophy to conquer the blindness of superstition.
</P>
<P>
Hong Xiaonan, associate professor at Dalian Engineering
University in northeast China's Liaoning Province, said that the
book "Wheel of Law" written by Li Hongzhi spread a doomsday theory
that is anti-human, anti-society, anti-government, and anti-
science.
</P>
<P>
The theory intends to wear down people's determination and make
them subservient to Li, he said, as Li aims to apotheosize himself
by playing the part of savior.
</P>
<P>
Song Jiaren, head of the branch hospital of the Medical College
of northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, noted that
Falun Gong spread an obvious fatalistic theory, one that goes
against medical science.
</P>
<P>
It regards illness as an adversity resulting from a previous
life, and the illness as the way of removing the adversity, he
said. As a result, many Falun Gong practitioners do not see
doctors or receive medical treatment while they are ill. This
delay of medical treatment in hospitals has lead to hundreds of
deaths, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Weiming, a senior engineer with the seismic bureau of
Ningxia, said that the theory of a global explosion and a coming
doomsday spread by Falun Gong is contrary to astronomic
observations and scientific results. The irresponsible idea that
only the practice of Falun Gong can help escape from these "
disasters" is just a daydream.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jisheng, a scientific official in Ningxia, emphasized
that it's worth pondering over the topic of the fatuity of Falun
Gong's superstitious activities, which are meant to take advantage
of people's desire for good health.
</P>
<P>
"We should strengthen the promotion of scientific knowledge
among the people to overcome fatuous superstition," the official
noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Using Scientific Philosophy to Conquer Fatalistic Theory of Falun Gong: Officials and People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two scientific researchers in north China's Shanxi Province,
who published an article critical of the fatalism of Falun Gong,
pointed out that this fatalistic theory is an attempt by Li to
make practitioners believe that he can dominate people's fate and
that they all must be controlled by him. He wants to realize his
ulterior political purpose by obtaining eminent domain over people
's mind and spirit.
</P>
<P>
Guan Zhiwei, a former Falun Gong practitioner, said he withdrew
from the practice of Falun Gong last June and supports the central
government's ban on the illegal organization.
</P>
<P>
Guan, a medic in south China's Guangdong Province, said he
realized the true face of Li Hongzhi from a series of illegal
activities organized by Li such as attacks on news media units and
governmental departments.
</P>
<P>
Li always played the savior and let us worship him, Guan said,
this demonstrates that Falun Gong's nature is based on fatalism.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar attended by scientists and educators in Chongqing
Municipality in southwest China, the experts and scholars strongly
condemned the fatalistic theory of Li Hongzhi and said they will
insist on teaching students a Marxist scientific world view.
</P>
<P>
Falun Gong fallacies will have no corner to exist on campus,
and with wider popularization of modern scientific and
technological knowledge, more and more people will see clearly the
true nature of Falun Gong, they concluded.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Beijing today hosted a seminar attended
by 40 medical experts who refuted Li Hongzhi and Falun Gong. They
called on people to receive timely medical treatment when they
fall ill, and rid themselves of the deception and malicious cult
of Falun Gong through promoting scientific knowledge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
