<HEADLINE> 11 Military Personnel Killed in PKK Attacks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Eleven military personnel were
killed in attacks by the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
late Friday night in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A group of PKK rebels killed six village guards and wounded
another when they accompanied four telecommunication workers to
fix telephone in the Kirkgecit village of Gurpinar town of van
province that borders Iran, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Later, the PKK rebels released the telecommunication workers
they captured in the attacks, it added.
</P>
<P>
The agency also said that five soldiers were killed and 13
others wounded when a military vehicle hit a mine, planted by the
PKK near Kirkgecit village.
</P>
<P>
The military vehicle hit the mine on its way to reinforce the
village guards, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
It added that the injured were rushed to Van Military Hospital
by helicopter for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. The PKK attacks on
government targets continue after PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was
sentenced to death by Turkey's Ankara State Security Court last
June.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts between the Turkish security forces and the PKK
rebels have claimed over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
