<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handwritten Instructions Show Evidence of Falun Gong Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- A newly discovered application
carrying handwritten instructions by Falun Gong founder Li Hongzhi
approving the establishment of a Falun Gong guidance group in
Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, has provided
fresh evidence for the fact that Falun Gong has a tight
organization.
</P>
<P>
The instructions, written on April 15, 1994 on the margin of
the application for Li's approval of the establishment of the
Nanhua District Falun Gong Guidance Group submitted by a group of
Falun Gong practitioners in Nanjing, read: "I agree that you set
up a Falun Gong guidance group in your district. You may contact
the general station in Wuhan." Wuhan is capital of central Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
An examination by the local public security department shows
that the instructions are in Li's own handwriting.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Jiafang, Ran Yinluo, and Zang Chunlei, all
former members of the group, about 70 Falun Gong practitioners
from Nanjing, led by Liu Ruwen, a retired doctor, went to Hefei,
capital of east China's Anhui Province, to attend Falun Gong
courses given by Li Hongzhi in April 1994. On April 15 of the same
month, Liu submitted the application to Li who gave the approval
the same day.
</P>
<P>
China's central government banned Falun Gong as an illegal cult
on July 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
Investigations indicate that Falun Gong was not registered
according to law and had been engaged in illegal activities,
advocating superstition and spreading malicious fallacies,
hoodwinking people, inciting and creating disturbances, and
jeopardizing social stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
