<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 31 (Xinhua) -- China today condemned recent
United States and British airstrikes against civilian targets in
Iraq, according to Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the U.S. and Britain have continuously launched
airstrikes on civilian targets in the no-fly zones in southern and
northern parts of Iraq in recent days, causing serious casualties
and property loss, and noted that China condemns this.
</P>
<P>
China believes that the U.S. and British military action
against Iraq is not conducive to the settlement of the Iraqi issue,
and has also called for an immediate halt to the military action,
Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in favor of the establishment of the no-fly zones
in Iraq, and we hold that Iraq's sovereignty and territorial
integrity should be fully respected, and that the Iraqi issue
should be peacefully solved based on the U.N. Charter, the
relevant U.N. resolutions, and norms governing international
relations," the spokesman stated.  
