<HEADLINE> 18th Century Slave Skulls Unearthed in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has unearthed eight
skulls of human beings and an assortment of bones believed to
belong to victims of the slave trade in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
The remains have been unearthed from a grave in Pangani town,
some 190 kilometers north of Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam, the
Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The skulls and bones were discovered in a one-meter-deep grave,
situated on a plot near the historical one-story building now
housing the District Education Office, less than 10 meters from
the seafront.
</P>
<P>
The remains were found when the Tanzania Telecommunications
Company Limited workers were digging a foundation for a telephone
tower.
</P>
<P>
The district cultural officer, Leonard Sekibaha, took a piece
of bone for examination in the northern town Moshi to determine
when the owner was buried, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Pangani, like Bagamoyo, was once a famous auction center for
the infamous slave trade and some relics of the horrible trade are
still available to date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
