<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arctic Expedition Team Discovers Anchored Buoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Scientists on the Snow
Dragon, the expeditionary vessel carrying 124 Chinese scientists
and journalists to the North Pole, discovered an anchored buoy
early today while on an inspection tour of the Bering Sea.
</P>
<P>
The buoy was later confirmed to be an ocean supervising device
that uses satellites to transmit data about the changing ocean
environment.
</P>
<P>
The buoy consists of two parts, one under water and a data
transmission antenna above the water, and is located at 59 degrees
14 minutes 59 seconds north latitude, and 178 degrees 46 minutes
47 seconds west longitude.
</P>
<P>
The number 70435 is printed on the buoy, and there is a signal
light on a small floating ball trailing behind the buoy. The buoy'
s anchor is believed to lie about 2,500-meter-deep in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
According to scientist Zhao Jinping aboard the ship, the
anchored buoy is mainly used to monitor sea changes for weather
forecasting.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese expedition team has already recorded the number,
location, and time of the discovery of the buoy for later
communications with any concerned foreign counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The expedition, China's first government-sponsored Arctic
expedition, will take more than two months to complete, with the
scientists aboard expected to return home in late September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
