<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Draws Up Guidelines for Satellite Campuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Universities
Commission has drawn up comprehensive guidelines for the
establishment of satellite campuses, study centers and
affiliations.
</P>
<P>
A source with the commission said that the guidelines which aim
at regulating the provision of tertiary education at satellite
campuses had been approved by the Nigerian government, This Day
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The existing satellite campuses and outreach stations and
affiliations are required to meet the provisions of the guidelines
before the end of September this year, the unidentified source
said.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines covers criteria for the establishment of an
outreach center, facilities, staffing, academic programs,
administrations, procedure for approval of an outreach center and
supervision of academic programs of an outreach center.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines provide that a center must be self-financing to
the extent that government subvention is not committed to such
outreach centers.
</P>
<P>
The admission requirements should conform to the minimum
academic standards for the relevant discipline while admission of
students must be documented with the Joint Admission Matriculation
Board.
</P>
<P>
Programs to be run at an outreach station must be those that
are approved and being run at the parent institution in order to
maintain the required academic standards and conform to the
requirements for full time programs, according to the guidelines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
