<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Lagos State Sees 839 Murders in 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The crime seemed to be on the rise
in the past years in Nigeria's economic hub Lagos state, with
police having officially listed at least 839 murder cases for the
period of 1990-97, The Guardian newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics released recently by police show that no fewer
than 378, 720 persons had been held as suspects, in connection
with 399,604 various criminal acts during the period.
</P>
<P>
The offenses range from murder and armed robbery to kidnapping,
rape and indecent assault, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The two major capital offenses - murder and armed robbery,
which usually attract death sentence, have seen a continuous
soaring in the past years, according to the police statistics.
</P>
<P>
The rising crime rate in Nigeria's major cities is a great
concern for the new civilian government, which has adopted such
measures as establish quick-action police force and expanding
police recruitment to combat the trend.
</P>
<P>
Poverty and years of corruptive rule of the military regimes
are believed to be at the root of the crime surge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
