<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Bans Sleazy Movies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's National Film and Censors
Board Friday issued a ban on locally packaged films with occult
themes in a bid to check the growing sleaze in video entertainment
and the negative influence on society.
</P>
<P>
Video productions banned by the board as having negative
cultural tendencies are those with themes on occultism and
cultism, fetishism, witchcraft, voodooism, devilish spiritualism,
uncontrolled tendency for sexual display, bloodiness, incest,
violence as well as poisoning, the Guardian newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
By that token, the stage seems set for tighter ethical control
of the burgeoning industry believed to be highly influential in
societal acculturation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached following the board's review of past
approvals, upon which it was discovered that films hitherto
brought for "registration, examination, assessment, analysis,
evaluation and classification" revolved mostly around negative
themes.
</P>
<P>
Movies already in the market without prior approval by the
board will henceforth be sanctioned in accordance with the
relevant laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to the censors board, films and production "which
continue to exploit mainly these themes or topics ... will no
longer receive approval for public release, in view of the obvious
imbalance."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the board is dissatisfied with the manner in which
several of the productions were packaged, particularly with the
"noticeable deficiencies or defect in their presentation".
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the censors board, Ademola James, said
that such films were purely motivated by the excessive desire for
profit by movie makers, marketers and investors.
</P>
<P>
"Pandering to unsavory public taste is not in consonance with
the artistic excellence and positive image projection which all
movie makers should strive to maintain," he noted
</P>
<P>
"Operators and practitioners who choose to defy this warning by
putting such negatively oriented movies in the market without
prior submission to the board will have the full weight of the law
applied against them," James said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
