<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unilever Confident of Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- We consider China a very large
potential market, and as a European enterprise with one of the
largest investments in the country, we expect a bright future,
Chris Mason, marketing manager of Unilever (China) Ltd., said here
today in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The original company, known as Lever Brothers, set up their
largest soap factory in the Far East in Shanghai as early as 1924,
and the modern company established Unilever (China) Ltd. on the
original factory site in 1986, the first Western enterprise
dealing in daily consumer products to return to the Chinese market
after China's implementation of the reform and opening-up policy
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The enterprise now has a number of joint ventures in Shanghai,
Beijing, Guangzhou, and Hefei, producing food and detergents. It
has also established a research center at the Shanghai Institute
of Organic Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
Unilever also signed an agreement with the Shanghai Municipal
government in 1997 on the establishment of a research fund,
offering 300,000 US dollars to the Shanghai Municipal Science and
Technology Commission over a three year period.
</P>
<P>
The success of Lux in the Chinese market shows that China has
become one part of the international market, said Chris Mason.
</P>
<P>
Lever Brothers, established in 1894 with headquarters in London
and Rotterdam, now has 300 cooperative firms in 90 countries
worldwide, with an annual sales volume exceeding 50 billion U.S.
dollars. The company was ranked tenth among the 500 largest
enterprises in 1998 in terms of net profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
