<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Popular Forces Conference Condemns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Arab Popular Forces
Conference on Friday concluded with a statement condemning
U.S.-British aggression on Iraq and continuation of
U.N. sanctions against the country.
</P>
<P>
The final session of the non-governmental organization's
meeting was attended by Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan,
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and other Iraqi senior officials,
the Iraqi News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the conference stressed that the
continuation of the U.S.-British aggression on Iraq and the
imposition of the so-called no-fly zones in northern and southern
Iraq contradict all international values and norms.
</P>
<P>
In the past two days, 17 Iraqi civilians were killed and
dozens of others injured in U.S. and British air raids on civil
and service installations in the two no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the
Security Council to live up to their legal and ethical
responsibilities and seriously work for the lifting of the embargo
on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Terming the continuation of the U.N. embargo on Iraq as an
"American decision," the statement said Arab nations should work
together to beat up the decision.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting demanded to put an end to the
American and British military presence in the Gulf which they said
targets the independence of regional countries.
</P>
<P>
They called for holding an Arab summit to draw up a strategy
for defending the interests and rights of the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the necessity of releasing Iraq's assets
frozen in Arab banks, the participants also urged the U.N. to
stop the deduction of the compensation sums and U.N. committee
costs from Iraqi oil revenues and allocate all Iraq's oil
revenues to meet its people's needs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which started on Friday evening, was initiated by
the Jordanian National Mobilization Committee in Defense of Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
