<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Send 60 Police Officers to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to send 60 Royal Ulster
Constabulary (RUC), Northern Ireland's police force, to help keep
order in Kosovo, a British newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 60 RUC men have been chosen because they are the British
policemen with the most appropriate experience, the Guardian said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike mainland British police, the RUC are accustomed to
routinely carrying weapons, patrolling with the military and
working with divided communities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Guardian, British Prime Minister Tony Blair,
who visited the Kosovo capital of Pristina on Friday, would make
an announcement about it on Saturday during another brief trip to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of Serbian forces has left the province without
a police service.
</P>
<P>
"We regard policing as a key function in Kosovo, and we want to
encourage others to follow suit and put people on the ground," a
British official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The relevant U.N. plans call for a force of 3,200 officers in
Kosovo. Member sates have already pledged 2,100, but only a
handful are in place in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
