<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Kill 124,000 in OECD Countries in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents killed 124,000
people and caused an economic loss of 450 billion U.S. dollars in
1998 in the member countries of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD), said OECD on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The loss inflicted by traffic accidents represented 2 percent
of the gross domestic product of these countries.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, which is a member of OECD, is not included in this
account, because of lack of statistics from the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
OECD represents the world's 29 most industrialized countries.
</P>
