<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Denies Presence of Pak Troops in Its Ranks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban has
dismissed reports that Pakistani troops are fighting alongside the
militia, but admitted presence of a few "Pakistani Taliban".
</P>
<P>
"There is no Pakistan soldiers in our ranks," said a statement
released Friday by the militia's spokesman Mulla Abdul Hayee
Motmain in Kandahar, Taliban's headquarters in southern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Motmain, however, admitted there are a few "Pakistani Taliban",
the Pakistani Islamists who follow Afghanistan's radical Taliban,
in the fighting against the anti-Taliban northern alliance in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
These Pakistani Taliban are "the mujahideen (holy war fighters)
who took part in Afghan war against Soviet occupation" in 1970s
and 1980s, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia, who control most of Afghanistan, has
launched a major offensive this week in a bid to wipe out the
northern alliance forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
