<HEADLINE> 2 Pro-Israeli Militiamen Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the pro-Israeli
South Lebanon Army (SLA) were wounded Friday night in south
Lebanon by Lebanese guerrillas' attacks, the militia's official
radio Voice of the South reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the two militiamen were injured by shrapnels of
shells fired at their post at Sujod in the central sector of the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Shiite Muslim group Amal led by House Speaker Nabih
Berri claimed responsibility for the attack, saying its fighters
launched rocket and machine-gun operations against a number of
Israeli posts Friday, scoring direct casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movements, including the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the pro-Syrian
Amal, have been fighting to oust Israeli forces and SLA out of the
country. 
</P>
