<HEADLINE> Mozambican Electoral Commission Suggests Polls in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican National Electoral
Commission has suggested that the country's next presidential and
parliamentary elections be held on December 3-4.
</P>
<P>
The commission said Friday that if necessary, the elections can
be postponed to December 4-5, the Noticias newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to Mozambique's election laws, the suggested date
would be effective only after the president of the republic
approves it.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the electoral commission, Maria Macuacua, told a
press conference in capital Maputo that the commission has made
the suggestion after comprehensive consideration.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican National Resistance, the largest opposition
party of the country, has reportedly expressed satisfaction with
the date suggested by the national electoral commission.
</P>
<P>
The first multi-party elections of the southern African country
were held in October, 1994. 
