<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Jordanians Get Minor Prison Terms for Alleged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Four Jordanians have been sentenced
to minor prison terms ranging from five to 12 months for killing
two women in separate incidents to cleanse their honor, the
semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Suleiman, 19, was sentenced to 12 months in prison
Thursday for killing his 21-year-old sister in February in the
southern Jordan Valley. His sister was six-month pregnant out of
the wedlock.
</P>
<P>
The court also handed down a five-month prison term to each of
another three men after declaring them guilty of murdering their
17-year-old relative Maha Walid in the Wadi Hajar district on
February 7.
</P>
<P>
The three men, who were Wadi's father, uncle and brother, shot
dead the girl for allegedly leaving home with strangers and
engaging in sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
Also, the girl's aunt, Tarfah Shehadeh received three months of
imprisonment for providing the gun used in the killing.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Jordanian young women died each year for alleged sex
affairs in the so-called honor killings, which were often carried
out by their fathers, brothers, husbands or other male relatives.
</P>
<P>
However, the Code of Penalties of the kingdom pardons or
reduces the penalties for men convicted of the honor killing.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from human rights groups, a special committee
under the Ministry of Justice has proposed to remove the clauses
in the code which it said benefited the honor killers.
</P>
<P>
The move has yet to be approved by the parliament and then by
a royal decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0127 </DOCNO>
