<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Strives for Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- When Joseph Estrada took oath as
Philippines' President on June 30 last year, he promised to
eradicate poverty of the country during his six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Over one more year passed, what has his government done for
some 20 million poor Filipinos?
</P>
<P>
As two-thirds of the country's poor people live in rural areas,
the most important aspect of the government's poverty eradication
program is to transform the country's agriculture and fisheries
into "technologically advanced and globally competitive sectors."
</P>
<P>
A major measure to realize this object is to expand linkage
between farms and markets, and between rural and urban areas,
through construction of roads, power, transport,
telecommunications and other infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
In the past one year, the government built 582 kilometers of
roads and 10,069 lineal meters of bridges, provided electricity to
1,221 villages and installed 165,000 new telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
The government also distributed more than 266,000 hectares of
land to 175,000 landless farmers to accelerate the country's land
redistribution process under the agrarian reform program.
</P>
<P>
The second measure is to help the poorest families in the
country. The government has identified 100 poorest families in
each province and city and asked concerned government agencies and
the private sector to set up livelihood programs for them.
</P>
<P>
The third measure is to provide teachers, policemen, soldiers,
government employee, wage earners and squatter families with
"decent, affordable shelters."
</P>
<P>
To carry out the housing plan, the government allocated 80
percent of it's housing funds to the poorest sector of the
population and only 20 percent to those who can afford to buy
housing units, a reversal of the previous administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
In line with this commitment, the government has set aside
about 21 billion pesos (525 million U.S. dollars) for its
socialized housing program.
</P>
<P>
From July 1998 to March 1999, the government provided 127,886
units of housing assistance which benefited some 74,000
households.
</P>
<P>
The government is also pushing for the passage by the congress
of a measure that would increase the capital of the Home Insurance
Guarantee Fund from 2.5 billion pesos (62.5 million dollars) to 50
billion pesos (1.25 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, the government reoriented the country's preferences
towards industries, enterprises and technologies to provide more
job opportunities for the poor.
</P>
<P>
For example, the government is paying more attention to
encouraging investments in labor-intensified small and
medium-scale industries, specially in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The fifth aspect Measure is to provide more education
opportunity for poor children. During the past year, the
government held 1,500 pre-school classes for poor kids in the
country's 20 faraway provinces, enabling almost 100,000
five-year-old kids to attend preschool classes free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The government likewise spent 760 million pesos (19 million
dollars) to help 380,000 kids go to private high schools and is
now working on a plan to provide textbooks for other cash-strapped
students.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is confident that through the
implementation of the pro-poor policies, more poor Filipino masses
will be placed in the mainstream of national development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
