<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Launches HIV/AIDS Action in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has launched a
strategic plan aimed at reinforcing action against HIV/AIDS in
Africa, citing that the scourge is not only affecting health but
development.
</P>
<P>
Harold Wackman, the World Bank's Kenya country director, said
that the institution is putting HIV/AIDS at the center of its
development agenda through the plan entitled "Intensifying Action
against HIV/AIDS in Africa: Responding to a Development Crisis."
</P>
<P>
The plan will help to increase resources and technical support
for HIV/ AIDS prevention efforts, to inform African countries with
expanded knowledge of AIDS and push HIV/AIDS into the center of
national agendas.
</P>
<P>
"More than 11 million Africans have died, and another 22
million are now living with HIV/AIDS. This is two-thirds of all
the cases on the earth," the Daily Nation newspaper Saturday
quoted Wackman as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The 21 countries with the highest HIV prevalence in the world
are in Africa," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He warned that AIDS was swiftly undoing the development
achievements of African countries in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Wackman attributed ignorance, inaction and lack of resources to
the deteriorating spread of the HIV/AIDS epidemic in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0135 </DOCNO>
