<P>
The Environmental Protection and Pollution Control Act is being
amended to empower inspectors of the Environmental Council of
Zambia to arrest and prosecute companies and individuals
defrauding the environmental regulations, said Harrington.
</P>
<P>
Anyone found in illegal timber dealings would pay fines,
according to an amended act.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Saturday quoted the minister as
saying that other types of punishment were being discussed by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Harrington said that the act enacted in 1990 did not empower
the environmental council to arrest. This had rendered the
council toothless, thereby making the environment vulnerable to
degradation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said this had in turn made serious threats to
bio-diversity in the southern African country and that the economy
was under serious threat because it depended on the environment.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the new act which would be presented in
Parliament soon would help solve the problem through the powers to
be vested in the environmental council.
</P>
<P>
He said the amendment would serve as model to meet
socio-economic development needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
Harrington bemoaned the high number of companies breaking the
environmental regulations, saying that the new regulation was
required to provide a permanent control mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Deficit Stands at 22.7 Billion HK Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong recorded a deficit of
22.7 billion HK dollars (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) in the first
three months of the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Saturday in its financial results for the
three months ended June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure for the first three months of the current financial
year amounted to 59,504.3 million HK dollars (7,628.8 million U.S.
dollars) and revenue to 36,762.1 million HK dollars (4,713.1
million U.S. dollars), resulting in a deficit of 22,742.2 million
HK dollars (2,915.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fiscal reserves stood at 411,560.2 million HK dollars (52,
764.1 million U.S. dollars) by June 30, a decrease of 22,742.2
million HK dollars compared with the balance of 434,302.4 million
HK dollars (55,679.8 million U.S. dollars) on March 31, 1999, the
end of the previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said that the government's accounts were
prepared on a cash basis and reflected the incidence of receipts
and payments during the period.
</P>
<P>
"The results remain in line with our expectations, based on the
budgeted deficit for the year of 36.5 billion HK dollars (4.7
billion U.S. dollars) as announced by the financial secretary in
his Budget Speech on March 3," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
