<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 07:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Prepares National Plan to Combat Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will spend 22 million
Jordanian dinars (some 30.8 million U.S. dollars) in a three-year
national action plan to combat drug abuses and trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The plan, prepared by the National Higher Committee to Combat
Drugs, is also aimed at rehabilitating drug addicts and launching
public education campaigns against drugs, Jordan Times reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be carried out by the committee in close
cooperation with police, ministries of health, administrative and
social development.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Jordan will also put its borders under
stricter control and strengthen its cooperation with Arab and
international agencies involved in the battle against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has witnessed a rise in the number of drug abusers, and
at least 16 people died during the past three years due to
narcotics overdoses, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The use of hashish is common among drug abusers because of its
relatively low costs, but heroin abuse has also been on the rise
among Jordanians in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Police seized 54 kilograms of hashish, seven kilograms of
heroin, 62 kilograms of opium in May and June alone this year.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials blamed the rise in drug abuses on the lack
of family control over the youngsters, failure of educational
campaigns to promote public awareness of the dangers of drugs and
the growing problem of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate of the desert kingdom stood at more than
16 percent annually in the 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
