<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montenegro May Hold Referendum on Standing in Yugoslavia: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, 30 July (Xinhua) -- President Milo Djukanovic of the
Yugoslav Republic of Montenegro declared in Sarajevo Friday that
the Republic of Montenegro may hold a referendum on its standing
in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Montenegro will soon present guiding principles
to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to help re-define relations
with it, Djukanovic said. The basic principles are "equal
participation, democracy and legal system within the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia does not
accept the principles, a referendum will be held to decide the
Republic of Montenegro's "legal standing."
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic said the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia should open
to the European integration. The Republic of Montenegro insists on
establishing an "open, democratic and multi-nationality country"
so as to join the integration of Europe either with Serbia or
alone.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic was invited to participate in the Southeast Europe
Stability Pact Summit in Sarajevo, but Yugoslavian President
Slobodan Milosevic was excluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
