<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Enjoys Harvest Day at Pan American Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Cuba enjoyed a harvest
day while the traditional force United States suffered a shutout
defeat on the last day of the athletics competitions of the 13th
Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
But the Cuban triumph on the athletics field, which saw them
rush in half of the ten golds at stake, inflicted little impact in
the medals standings, with the United States still taking a firm
grip on the top place with a total of 62 golds.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and Canada are still battling out for the second place,
with the former taking a temporary lead on a 32-26-28 record.
Canada was third with a 28-29-36.
</P>
<P>
With the Pan Am athletics competitions wrapped up here today,
Cuba has taken the place of the United States as the No.1 track
and field country in the Americas. The Cuban athletes churned out
a total of 11 golds, against 10 for the United States, to lead the
final athletics medals table.
</P>
<P>
The United States, mostly composed of second-choice athletes,
had a nightmare in University of Manitoba Stadium today, denied
any accesses to what might be called their back-yard territory.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's five golds were even more remarkable as three of them
were companied by Pan Am record-breaking performances, from the
women's 100m hurdles, men's 110m hurdles and men's 4X400m relay
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the glamour event of men's 4X100m relay, Brazil achieved a
stunning win over the heavily-favored Olympic champions Canada,
shattering the 24-year-old Games record to win gold in 38.18.
</P>
<P>
Canada, with former men's 100m world record holder Donovan
Bailey running the first leg, came in a disappointing second
before a packed home crowd at University of Manitoba Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica established a new Games record to chalk up the gold in
the women's 4X100m relay, winning in 42.62 against the old best
time of 42.90. And in the men's 4X400m relay, the Jamaican
foursome squeezed the Pan Am record down to 2:57.97 to take the
gold.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the United States struck two more golds and
Guatemala broke duck in the medal count when the Pan Am shooting
competitions wrapped up here today.
</P>
<P>
On a day which saw the rawing competitions concluded, South
American rowing force Argentina came ashore with a pair of golds,
boosting their medals tally to eight.
</P>
<P>
In cycling, the United States wheeled away three more cycling
golds while Canada's so-called "Golden Girl" Tanya Dubnicoff
followed her 500m time trial win on Tuesday with a women's sprint
gold, driving the packed crowd at the Red River Exhibition Park to
a boisterous ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
In the finals of water polo, Canada beat the United States for
women's title while the American men's team made a late
consolation by defeating Cuba 11-7 to win gold.
</P>
<P>
In the volleyball semi-finals, Cuba beat their bitter rivals
the United States 25-20, 25-21, 25-23 to reach the final, where
they faces Brazil, a 25-20, 25-13, 25-12 winner over the Dominican
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
