<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Bank Floats Industrial Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 31 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's nationalized Agrani
Bank has floated a bond to raise 5 billion taka (about 101 million
U.S. dollars) as part of a government program to finance new
industrial ventures.
</P>
<P>
The step taken by the government followed a prolonged liquidity
crunch in most local banks blamed on huge amount of bad debt and
low rates of savings, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first step of the government's plan to raise the
:;44:93@@6.84
capital for industrialization, Finance Minister A.M.S. Kabria was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We will expand the program after assessment of the success of
the project and hope to raise the amount to 20 billion taka (about
404 million dollars) by next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
One fourth of the bond will be directly invested by the Agrani
Bank while others will use the rest of the capital for lending
money for industries on a long-term basis, he said, calling upon
all people including industrialists to avail the attractive
package for their own profit and benefit of the country.
</P>
<P>
The savings rate in Bangladesh is lower than in neighboring
India and Pakistan, which has been a major constraint of
investment causing a "vicious cycle: low income-low savings-low
investment-low income," he observed.
</P>
<P>
The national savings rate has stagnated below 12 percent of the
country's 34 billion-dollar gross domestic product (GDP), and so
the banks have no enough capital for term investment, which
warranted the need for floating the bonds, the first ever in the
country, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Sonali Bank will also float next month dollar
bonds worth 100 million dollars for expatriate Bangladeshis in the
Middle East and elsewhere, a bank official disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
