<HEADLINE> Argentine, Brazilian Presidents to Discuss Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and visiting Argentine President Carlos Menem
have agreed to meet Wednesday in Montevideo to discuss ways to
resolve the two countries trade conflicts and promote bilateral
trade.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Argentina and Brazil grew tense after Buenos
Aires announced in July restrictions over imports from Brazil,
involving textile and steel products, electric appliances, paper
and shoes.
</P>
<P>
The Argentines adopted protectionist measures in order to
protect its trade balance from an onslaught of Brazilian imports
made cheaper by the mid-January devaluation of Brazil's currency,
the real.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Brazil reacted by temporarily suspending trade talks
with Argentina
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Argentine government and the opposition agreed
to support the accord reached by presidents Menem and Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the disputes between the two member countries
have thrown the fledgling Mercosur customs union into one of its
worst crises since it went into effect in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, or the Southern Common Market, comprises Brazil,
Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay. Bolivia and Chile are associate
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
