<HEADLINE> Cuba Receives Authorization to Sell Meningitis Vaccine to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States has authorized
the sale of a Cuban vaccine against meningitis type B to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba has never prevented the United states (from purchasing
the vaccine)," local media quoted Cuban Public Health Minister
Carlos Dotres as saying. It would be an injustice for children,
the main victims of the disease, to do so, he added.
</P>
<P>
The media reports said that Smithkline Beecham PLC, a British
pharmaceutical company, announced that after one year and a half
of talks, Washington finally agreed to authorize the Cuban vaccine
for sale in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Smithkline has laboratories in Belgium, which are owned by a
United States branch, which are subject to prohibition decrees
against Cuba by the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the British firm will form a joint
enterprise with the Carlos J. Finlay Institute of Havana after the
license is granted by the U.S. Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. expert said in July last year that adequate development
and marketing of the Cuban vaccine would prevent 1,000 to 2,000
cases of meningitis B from developing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Dotres said that Cuban scientists developed the VAMENGOC-BC,
the only effective vaccine in the world against the disease in
1985, and it is considered by many investigators as the most
advanced product against meningitis type-B.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has sold millions of doses of that vaccine since that time
to several countries including Argentina, Brazil and Colombia.
</P>
</TEXT>
