<HEADLINE> Panamanian President Dismisses U.S. Congressmen's Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian President Ernesto
Perez Balladares rejected here Friday allegations by some U.S.
Congressmen that the Panama Canal is controlled by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The president said the allegations, quoted Friday by the local
press, lack objectivity and foundation.
</P>
<P>
Dana Rohrbacher, one of the congressmen, said the canal,
instead of reverting to Panama, is now in Chinese hands, referring
to investments by Hutchinson, a Hong Kong company, in Panamanian
ports, and the increase of business by the Chinese shipping
company COSCO in Panama.
</P>
<P>
"We are simply accustomed to those kinds of opinions, absurd in
many cases," the president told the press after an official
ceremony marking the withdrawal of the U.S. Army from this country,
held at the Fort Clayton military base.
</P>
<P>
Perez Balladares said Rohrbacher's opinion does not represent
the United States government's position at all.
</P>
<P>
These absurd remarks reflect a lack of intelligence, said Perez
Balladares.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian president defended the promotion of private
investments his government is successfully carrying out in areas
being returned to Panama by the United States since 1979.
</P>
<P>
The areas have attracted numerous investments from China, Spain,
the United States, Canada, Japan, Taiwan, and from Panamanian
investors to develop ports, tourism centers and industries.
</P>
<P>
The canal will completely revert to Panama from the United
States by the end of 1999, according to an agreement signed by the
two countries in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
