<HEADLINE> Brazil Upsets Canada to Win Men's 4X100 Relay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Shi Ting
</P>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Brazil shocked the
heavily-favored hosts Canada for an upset men's 4x100 relay
victory on an exciting evening of the Pan American athletics
finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian quartet shattered the 24-year-old Games record to
win the gold in 38.18, shaving 0.13 seconds off the previous best
mark set by the United States in the 1975 Mexico City Games.
</P>
<P>
Olympic and world champions Canada, with former men's 100m
world record holder Donovan Bailey running the first leg, came in
a disappointing second before a packed home crowd at the
University of Manitoba Stadium. Their time was 0.31 seconds short
of Brazil's.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica won the bronze at 38.82. The world record for the blue
riband event of athletics stood intact as 37.40, which was set by
the powerful U.S. squad seven years ago in the Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Defending Olympic champion Bailey, who was vilified in the
local media after turning down the invitation to run the men's
100m and not showing up in the opening ceremonies, failed to
redeem himself on what would have been a perfect opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica established a new Games record to chalk up the gold in
the women's 4x100m relay, winning in 42.62 against the old best
time of 42.90.
</P>
<P>
The United States was beaten into second place with a time of
43.27, Cuba following up in 43.52.
</P>
<P>
In the men's high jump, world record holder Javier Sotomayor of
Cuba won an expected gold, but his 2.30m winning mark was no match
for the world record of 2.45m he set six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor's woman teammate A.Y. Lopez Pedroso posted a new
Games record of 12.76 seconds to win the women's 100m hurdles
while men's 110 hurdles race also saw a record-breaking
performance, with another Cuban Anier Garcia Ortiz winning in 13.
17.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 1,500m race, home favorite Graham Hood contributed
only the second athletics gold to the host Canada. T he unfancied
athlete made a move in the last 200 meters, crossing the line with
a personal best of three minutes 41.20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 4x400m relay, the Jamaican foursome squeezed the
Pan American record down to 2:57.97 to take the gold, Brazil
following second with its season's best mark of 2:58.56 and the
world record holders the United States third with a dismal 3:00.94.
</P>
<P>
Cuba registered the squad's best time of 3:26.70 to win the
women's 4x400m relay.
</P>
<P>
Women's discus gold went to Brazil's E.M. Adriano, whose mighty
toss turned out to be her personal best of 60.92 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
