<HEADLINE> Colombian President Reaffirms Commitment for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres Pastrana
said Friday that his government will continue to maintain its
commitment for peace despite the standstill in talks with the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Spanish daily "El Pais," Pastrana said
that he and Manuel Marulanda, the top leader of the rebel
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), "are willing to sit
down and to negotiate."
</P>
<P>
"There is a personal commitment between Marulanda and I" for
peace, said Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Colombian government and FARC, the
largest rebel group in the country, started at the beginning of
the year, but they were suspended after the cancellation of the
dialogue scheduled for July 19 during a strong guerrilla offensive.
</P>
<P>
The president said he is confident that the guerrillas would
declare in December a cease-fire as a peace gesture.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana reiterated rejection to foreign intervention in
Colombia in response to reports of a possible incursion of U.S.
forces against the guerrillas and drug traffickers in Colombia. He
also rejected the view that the guerrillas and the drug
traffickers are the same people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
