<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Outer Space Meeting Ends With Vienna Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The third U.N. outer space meeting
ended here Friday with the passing of a Vienna Declaration on
Space and Human Development.
</P>
<P>
Space experts from around the globe gathered here to discuss
the more reasonable and more comprehensive usage of new space
technologies in the coming new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The key themes of the Vienna Declaration, which was released at
the end of the two-week meeting, included environmental protection,
resources management, the use of space technologies to promote
human security and welfare, and the improvement of training and
education on outer space activities.
</P>
<P>
The declaration stressed the need to strengthen and adjust U.N.
outer space activities, and promote international cooperation in
this field.
</P>
<P>
Participants also agreed to propose a World Space Week from
October 4-10, hold an international outer space meeting every five
years, and establish a U.N. special funds for space research.
</P>
<P>
Luan Enjie, Director of the Chinese State Aerospace Bureau,
also head of the Chinese delegation, briefed the assembly on China
's recent development in the aeronautic and space field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
