<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Establishes First Securities Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bao Viet Securities Company, the
first of its kind in Vietnam, has been set up by the Vietnam
Insurance Corporation (Bao Viet).
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Vietnam's securities company, according to
a report of the official news agency VNA on Friday, was under a
permit of Vietnam's State Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
The company has a statutory capital of 43 billion Vietnamese
dong (3.07 million U.S. dollars), to which Bao Viet contributed 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
The capital will be divided into 4.3 million shares, issued as
bearer or registered securities.
</P>
<P>
The company will take part in securities brokerage, trade,
management of invested portfolio, underwriting and consultancy.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to be put into operation late this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Army Headquarters Moves from Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Southern Command bases
along the banks of the Panama Canal were removed from the Central
American country on Friday after 88 years of the U.S. military
presence.
</P>
<P>
"With the departure of the South Army, our mutually-benefited
relationship with the Panama Republic concludes," General
Commander of the U.S. Southern Command Charles Wilhelm said in a
closing ceremony at the parade ground on Soldier's Field in Fort
Clayton.
</P>
<P>
Wilhelm's Southern Command, the administrative head for all U.S.
armed services for the Latin America-Caribbean region, moved out
of Panama in 1997. Friday's ceremony ended the presence of U.S.
Army South in Panama. Those headquarters will move to Fort
Buchanan in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
Fewer than 1,000 U.S. military personnel remain in Panama, most
of them in the base at Corozal, an installation just south of
Clayton, near the Pacific entrance of the Panama Canal. Even these
soldiers are steadily departing week by week.
</P>
<P>
Until the mid 1990s, more than 10,000 U.S. army men were based
in Panama and every year some 7,000 to 8,000 passed through the
jungle combat training missions. At the height of the U.S.
presence, during World War II, about 65,000 U.S. troops were based
in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The first U.S. soldiers came to the country in 1903 and the
first U.S. soldiers permanently assigned came in 1911 to guard
construction efforts of the Panama Canal, which started in 1914.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1977 treaty signed by President Jimmy Carter and
Panamanian leader Omar Torrijos, the United States has been
gradually turning over its 183,000 hectares of holdings in the
Canal Zone and military bases to Panama.
</P>
<P>
Major bases, such as the army's Fort Sherman and the air force'
s Albrook installations, have already been handed over, along with
most of the Panama Canal headquarters, installations and
residences.
</P>
<P>
There are only a few hundred U.S. soldiers remaining in the
country until the Panama Canal is handed over at the end of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
