<HEADLINE> Argentina Comes off More Rowing Victories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 30 (Xinhua) -- South American rowing
force Argentina came ashore with a pair of golds here today,
boosting their medals tally to eight on a day which saw Pan Am
rowing competitions conclude.
</P>
<P>
In the men's lightweight quadruple sculls, Argentine quartet
Ariel Zeller, Ulf Lienhard, Sebastian Massa and Mario Cejas
covered the 2,000m course with a time of five minutes 59.04
seconds, 0.19 seconds ahead of a strong Cuban team.
</P>
<P>
Their women counterparts enjoyed a more comfortable win,
turning in a time of 6:39.14, with the United States finishing a
well-beaten second place at 6:41.88.
</P>
<P>
Argentina has garnered up seven golds and one silver from the
rowing competitions at Lake Minnedosa, 250km from downtown
Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
The hosts Canada also had a great day, rowing to two victories
here today, delighting more than 2,000 spectators packed around
the lake.
</P>
<P>
D. Nesbitt-Porter scored a crushing victory to take out the men
's single sculls event, finishing in 6:54.50 to second-placed
American Aquail Abudllah's 7:00.27, while L.Biensenthal and her
partner J.Browett clocked 7:03.43 to win in the women's double
sculls.
</P>
<P>
But the highlight of the day came from the last competition,
men's cox eight sculls. The United States netted their third gold
of the rowing event by powering to victory in 5:33.50. 
</P>
