<HEADLINE> Against Three U.S. Golds, Canadian Golden Girl Triumphs Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States wheeled
away three more cycling golds while Canada's so-called "Golden
Girl" Tanya Dubnicoff came on target again here in the 13th Pan Am
Games.
</P>
<P>
Winnipegger Dubnicoff, the soon-turned national darling and Pan
Am Games flag bearer, followed her 500m time trial win on Tuesday
with a women's sprint gold, driving the packed crowd at the Red
River Exhibition Park to a boisterous ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old veteran cyclist, who is leading the cycling
World Cup overall standings, is the most successful female in the
history of Canadian track cycling.
</P>
<P>
As eight-time Canadian champion, Dubnicoff has won two Pan Am
gold medals (1991, 1995), two Commonwealth Games gold (1994, 1998).
She won the 1993 World Championship in sprint cycling after just 5
months in the sport.
</P>
<P>
The men's sprint gold went to former top-ranked cyclist Martin
Nothstein while his American teammates also notched up men's 4,000
team pursuit title with a time of four minutes 20.240 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old upstart Erin Veenstra led throughout to clinch
the women's 3,000m individual pursuit title, with Colombian Maria
Calle a distant second at 3:51.309. 
</P>
