<HEADLINE> Manchester United Fury at New Sports Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- English football club Manchester
United are adamant they will not play in next season's FA Cup
despite the new Sports Minister Kate Hoey expressed hopes they
would reverse their decision to pull out.
</P>
<P>
And United chief executive Martin Edwards dismissed as "
disgraceful" accusations that the club have treated their
supporters "shabbily".
</P>
<P>
The Treble-winners withdrew from the FA Cup to take part in the
FIFA-organised World Club Championship in Brazil in January.
</P>
<P>
Ms Hoey, who took over from Tony Banks on Thursday, insisted
that it was "imperative" that United defend the trophy.
</P>
<P>
But a defiant Edwards responded: "We won't be having a re-think.
We made the decision weeks ago and that decision stands.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't just our decision, it was a joint decision with both
the Government and the Football Association.
</P>
<P>
"For a new Sports Minister to suddenly enter the arena at this
late stage and tell us we are treating our supporters shabbily and
should go back in the FA Cup is a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
"I suggest she does her homework and I suggest the Government
gets its act together, because we did this in support of the last
Sports Minister."
</P>
<P>
Mr Banks had strongly defended United's decision to pull out of
the competition, but Ms Hoey immediately nailed her colours to a
different mast
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio 5 Live, Ms Hoey said: "I think it is
something that should not be happening. Manchester United should
be playing in the FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
"I still hope that something will happen that will make them
able to play in it after all.
</P>
<P>
"I am just amazed that they have actually treated their
supporters in what I would say was quite a shabby way."
</P>
<P>
But she added: "The people I really criticise are the FA. The
FA can still put matters right by saying to Manchester United they
must play in the FA Cup."
</P>
<P>
The FA threw down the gauntlet to Ms Hoey to offer a solution
to United's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"We remain open-minded as to the solution," FA spokesman Steve
Double said.
</P>
<P>
"However what is important, above all, is that somebody must
present a viable solution.
</P>
<P>
"Our stance has always been that we are open-minded on it.
United have stated publicly that do not want to enter a weakened
team in the Cup," the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
