<HEADLINE> World Records Remain Intact in Stockholm Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Three Kenyans failed to realize
their goals of breaking the world records at the Grand Prix here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japheth Kumuati clocked 2:15.45, namely 3.27 seconds shy of the
oldest record of two minutes 12.18 seconds in the 1,000 meters set
by British Sebastian Coe in Oslo on July 11,1981.
</P>
<P>
Noah Ngeny ran to his victory in 4:47.88, but failed to break
the 1,500m record by a margin of 2.20 seconds set by Algerian
Noureddine Morceli in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Paul Tergat was also off the pace as he attempted to eclipse
Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie's 10,000 meters mark of 26:22.75.
However, he still won in 27:10.08.
</P>
<P>
But Sweden's Olympic and world champion Ludmila Engquist, who
has been battling breast cancer for more than a year, delighted a
cheering home crowd by winning the 100 meters hurdles in 12.68
seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I felt that the whole of Sweden was with me today and with
that sort of support I knew I couldn't fail," said the 35-year-old
Russian-born athlete.
</P>
<P>
American sprint queen Marion Jones romped home to her 19th
successive victory, but was dismissive of her 22.07 win in the 200
metres.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Michael Johnson's world championship hopes
were in doubt after he pulled up clutching his thigh less than
midway through the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Maurice Greene easily won the 100 meters in
9.87 seconds from Obadele Thompson of Barbados.
</P>
<P>
Other highlights included a strong showing from South African
Hestrie Storbeck-Cloete, who won the women's high jump with a 1.97
metre leap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
