<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek-Turkish Talks to Continue in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Turkey agreed here
Friday to hold the next round of their talks at senior officials'
level in September.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued here, senior foreign ministry
officials of the two countries said that they would hold the next
round of talks in September over the same issues after a prior
review of the ideas and proposals put forward by each side
separately.
</P>
<P>
On July 26 and 27, senior diplomats of the two neighboring
countries held the first round of their talks in Ankara, Turkey,
on the issues of tourism, the environment, trade and economic
cooperation while the second round of such talks took place in
Athens on July 29 and 30 on combating organized crime, illegal
immigration, drug-trafficking and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said in the joint communique that their talks in
Ankara and Athens were held in "a positive, professional and
relaxed atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
They agreed on the target of close cooperation in the fields
under discussion. To that end they exchanged views and reviewed
the possibilities of promoting that cooperation in a specific
manner.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds for
decades over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The talks, the first at this level since 1994, were agreed to
in late June between the Greek and Turkish foreign ministers,
George Papandreou and Ismail Cem.
</P>
<P>
Although Greece has agreed to begin talks with Turkey, it has
refused to discuss with Ankara the issues concerning Athens'
sovereignty over the eastern Aegean Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
