<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDCP Uses Satellite Remote Sensing to Detect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
International Drug Council Program (UNDCP) Friday announced that
it has designated a plan to use remote sensing (RS) and other
space-related technologies to monitor the illicit cultivation of
narcotic crops, particularly the opium poppy and the coco bush
which feed the international drug trade.
</P>
<P>
Initial findings of a joint project, conducted by UNDCP and the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization in 1993 and 1994,
established that it was possible to monitor the growth of illicit
crops with the aid of RS technologies.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, satellite-based platforms have been developed
and launched which, combined with new innovative image processing
technologies, provide the opportunity to produce accurate high
resolution images enabling the identification of illicit crops at
an economically viable cost.
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations General Assembly Special Session on the
World Drug Problem in June 1998, Member States decided to work
closely with UNDCP to create strategies to eliminate or
significantly reduce illicit cultivation of the opium poppy,
cannabis and coco bush by the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
The Member States requested the UNDCP to intensify the
collection and analysis of previously incomplete data the extent
of these crops, to aid their elimination strategy and measure its
progress.
</P>
<P>
Taking up the challenge, UNDCP developed a program to establish
an International Network for the Monitoring of Narcotic Crops by
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The objective is to enable countries affected by illicit
cultivation to assess growth levels of narcotic crops and
determine trends at a national level.
</P>
<P>
During the now completed first phase of this program, UNDCP
reached an agreement with the European Space Agency to place
satellite imagery technology at the disposal of governments for the
purpose of monitoring illicit crops.
</P>
<P>
Some economies of scale were achieved, thus minimizing the cost
of developing RS technology for user countries, UNDCP said. The
provision of technical assistance tailored to the individual needs
of governments is envisaged in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The International Network for the Monitoring of Narcotic
Crops will also validate the methods of monitoring the
cultivation of coca and opium plants with satellite-procured
imagery. It will formulate guidelines for their use in addition
to identifying ways of controlling the quality of the data
obtained.
</P>
<P>
Following this study, governments should be better able to
assess the feasibility, modalities, needs and not lease of all,
the financial requirements for using satellite remote sensing
technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Involve in Balkan Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
here Friday that his country is "making a commitment to take
generous, immediate, and unilateral steps to improve market access
for products made in southeast Europe".
</P>
<P>
"I will work with the United States Congress to establish a
trade preference program similar to our Andean initiative, which
will offer duty-free treatment for most of the region's exports,"
he told world leaders here attending the so-called Stability Pact
Summit through a written statement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said nations in the region should be brought into the
World Trade Organization on commercially acceptable terms, and be
provided the technical assistance they need to meet those terms.
</P>
<P>
He also called for promoting private investment in the region's
economies, and supporting the development of the region's private
sector. "To that end, America's Overseas Private Investment
Corporation will establish a 150-million-US-dollar investment fund
for the region and a 200-million-US-dollar credit line," he said.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (EBRD), the United States will set up a trust fund
designed to help businesses in the southeast Europe become more
competitive and viable, said Clinton. But he said his
administration would first consult with the Congress.
</P>
<P>
"We would be willing to contribute 15 million dollars in the
first year, and to consider up to 50 million dollars overall, as
long as the EBRD targets an additional 80 million dollars for the
region," he detailed the American plan.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we will support the creation of a regional equity
fund of up to 300 million dollars, with financing from the
international financial institutions, to make equity investments
in private enterprises in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president also indicated the incoming action by his
administration. "Our Commerce Secretary William Daley will also
sponsor a mission to the region to showcase trade and investment
opportunities and build new business partnerships," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here hold that the United States is ready to deeply
involve in the economic reconstruction process in Balkan region
through various action plans which were modeled as western powers'
anti-Communism Mashall Plan for rebuilding Europe after the second
World War.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from major western countries and Balkan nations and
heads of main international organizations ended the Stability Pact
Summit this afternoon after issuing a Declaration calling for
integration of Balkans into a single European model. The Stability
Pact, which was initiated and already adopted by the European
Union, has been widely regarded as a new Mashall Plan to promote
western ideology, value and way of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Depleted Uranium "Threatens Balkan Cancer Epidemic" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Americans' use of depleted
uranium (DU) weapons in Serbia is likely to cause extra deaths
from cancer, a British scientist warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
The use of depleted Uranium shells in Kosovo, fired mostly from
U.S. planes, was endangering the health of returning refugees,
peacekeepers, aid workers and the people of neighboring countries,
said Dr Roger Coghill, a British experimental biologist.
</P>
<P>
Coghill, who runs his own research laboratory in south Wales,
was speaking at a London conference discussing the links between
depleted uranium and cancers in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We know that some one million DU bullets were fired (during
the Gulf War) and many still lie in the Gulf desert, causing
clearly serious cancers and birth defects." he said, adding that
"The connection between the two is biologically extremely
plausible."
</P>
<P>
Coghill said there had been evidence in other parts of the
Balkans of elevated radiation levels during and soon after the
bombing of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Using calculations based on the Pentagon's statement, Coghill
estimated that half of the 500,000 depleted uranium rounds fired
over Kosovo detonated, which he said would have resulted in the
release of about one thirty-thousandth of the amount of radiation
released at Chernobyl in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Coghill said the maximum effect will be reached about six
months after the war, suggesting that the first cancers
</P>
<P>
may start to show up about a year after that.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the Balkan region, I calculate that there will be
an extra 10,150 deaths from cancer because of the use of depleted
uranium." he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
