<HEADLINE> Russia Wants Belgrade to Join Balkan Stability Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Friday that it wants
Yugoslavia to join the Stability Pact for Southeastern Europe as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Russia "intends to actively participate in the implementation
of the Stability Pact for Southeastern Europe, as it is one of its
co-authors," Foreign Ministry Spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most important conditions for the success of the
Pact is equal relations between all the countries in the region
without exception.
</P>
<P>
"In this connection, the Russian Federation wishes Yugoslavia
to join the Pact as soon as possible," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The pact, signed early June in Cologne, Germany, was designed
to help Albania, Romania, Bulgaria, Macedonia, Bosnia, Croatia and
Slovenia. Leaders and representatives from 45 countries were
meeting in Sarajevo, Bosnia, to formulate plans on the
reconstruction of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin also urged the international community to extend aid
to Yugoslavia, which suffered great damage under NATO's 78-day air
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The assistance should not be selective and discriminatory, or
Yugoslavia may face a very serious humanitarian catastrophe in the
Autumn and Winter, Rakhmanin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
