<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Stock Exchange To Become Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The London Stock Exchange (LSE) is
planning to scrap its status as a Mutual organization and become a
private company.
</P>
<P>
The LSE announced Friday that it would not initially sell
shares to the public, but the new structure would allow for
increased investment by dealers and others.
</P>
<P>
The organization, which has been a Mutual for 200 years will
stop short of floating shares in itself but will be privately
owned by its 294 member firms.
</P>
<P>
The plans follow a series of announcements by overseas stock
exchanges including the New York stock exchange and America's
Nasdaq market to turn themselves into shareholder-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The new structure was unanimously approved at a meeting of the
14 member board on Thursday. It is subject to approval by a vote
of the full membership of 294 shareholders, according to the
announcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Registers Trade Surplus in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The 11-nation euro zone has
registered a trade surplus with the rest of the world in May this
year, Eurostat reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau of the European community said that the
euro zone chalked up a trade surplus of 2.7 billion euro (2.8
billion U.S. dollars) compared with 5.4 billion euro (5.67 billion
U.S. dollars) in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The same month a year ago saw a trade surplus of 8.7 billion
euro (9.1 billion dollars) for the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The European statistical bureau also reported that the
15-nation European Union had registered a trade deficit of 1.4
billion euro (1.47 billion dollars) with the rest of the world in
May this year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the European Union posted a 3.3-billion-euro
trade surplus with the rest of the world in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The EU trade growth with most of its major trade partners was
weak or falling in the first four months of the year. EU exports
to China and Hungary were the exceptions. Exports to China and
Hungary both grew by 16 percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
The biggest drop in exports was registered in Russia where EU
exports decreased by 55 percent. The next sharpest drop was in
Norway at 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Helps to Demobilize Ex-Fighters in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations military
observers have carried out the temporary registration of 200
ex-combatants in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, a U.N.
spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference that the temporary registration was done by the United
Nations Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL) Military
Observers.
</P>
<P>
"Arrangements are underway for the transfer of Lungi, on the
other side of the estuary, where the complete registration and
disarmament, demobilization, reintegration program will be
conducted," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The three reception sites which had been set up temporarily in
Freetown to cater for the influx of ex-combatants are going to be
closed once they are moved to Lungi, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the United Nations was appealing for 35
million U.S. dollars to finance the disarmament of former rebel
soldiers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Silva said last week that the United Nations was appealing to
donors on behalf of Sierra Leone for an initial 35 million U.S.
dollars to demobilize, disarm and reintegrate the rebel soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
