<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former White House Aide Tripp Indicted For Wiretapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- After a yearlong investigation,
former White House aide Linda Tripp was indicted Friday for
secretly taping her phone conversations with Monica Lewinsky, a
former White House intern who admitted having an affair with
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
A Howard County grand jury in Maryland indicted Tripp on one
count of illegal interception of a phone conversation on December
22, 1997, after she allegedly had been told by her lawyer that the
ongoing taping was illegal, Maryland State Prosecutor Stephen
Montanarelli said.
</P>
<P>
Tripp, whose tapes led to impeachment of President Clinton,
becomes the only central figure in the Lewinsky scandal to face
criminal charge.
</P>
<P>
She also was charged with allegedly disclosing the contents of
that conversation to Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
Maryland law forbids the recording of phone conversations
without the consent of the other party. Illegal wiretapping is
punishable by up to five years in prison and a 10,000 dollars fine
for each offense.
</P>
<P>
Tripp gave the tapes to Independent Counsel Ken Starr under a
grant of immunity from federal prosecution, but that does not
protect her from prosecution by her home state.
</P>
<P>
Starr's investigation of Clinton's sexual relationship with
Lewinsky led to President Clinton's impeachment by the House and
trial in the Senate. Clinton was acquitted in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
Tripp, who made more than 20 hours of tapes from her home in
Maryland, testified for Starr's grand jury that she taped several
conversations in late 1997 even after an attorney told her it was
illegal.
</P>
<P>
Tripp, 49, said she began taping her friend's phone calls
to protect herself because she was being pressured by Lewinsky
to lie in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky, who became friends with Tripp when they both worked
at the Pentagon, wanted Tripp to deny knowledge of the sexual
relationship between Lewinsky and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Tripp's attorney, Joseph Murtha, asked that Tripp be allowed to
surrender voluntarily, rather than being arrested.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Scientist Warns Against Space Garbage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- There will be no way to the outer
space in 150 years if the space pollution continues unchecked, a
Russian scientist warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on the army and ecology, Doctor of Technical
Sciences Vladimir Lebedev said the outer space might close in 50
years if the pollution rates increase, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian military researchers, who have been studying the
problem of space litter for the past decade, believe that
"self-propelled spreading of space litter is possible in the
future."
</P>
<P>
A collision of two large artificial objects in space will
result in the creation of thousands of new, smaller artificial
objects.
</P>
<P>
Radar has detected about 8,000 objects with a diameter of over
10 centimeters in space, the experts said, adding that there are
70,000 objects with a diameter of one centimeter and more than 3.5
million objects with a diameter of less than 1 millimeter in
space.
</P>
<P>
However, Lebedev sees no easy way to tackle the space garbage
problem other than to "fasten tighter the bolts and nuts of
rocket-boosters." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990731.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 </DATE_TIME>
