<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Slump For Second Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks slumped Friday
for the second consecutive day amid continuing fears that the
Federal Reserve would raise interest rates to prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 136.14 at
10,655.15, adding to a 180-point drop Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A bigger-than-expected rise in labor costs in the second
quarter released by the Labor Department Thursday sparked sellings
in the stock market as the news led investors to believe that the
Federal Reserve would raise interest rates as a preventive measure
against rising prices. The sellings continued Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve already nudged short-term rates up by a
quarter of a point at the end of June and in the past several
days. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned that the
Federal Reserve would act "promptly and forcefully" to curb
inflation if the new data show that the pace of labor cost and
price increase will be picking up.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 12.31 at 1,328.72 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 1.52 at 2,638.49.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 4.74 at 626.07. But the American
Stock Exchange index rose 3.64 at 788.23 and the Russell 2000
index of smaller companies rose 3.19 at 444.77.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,530 up, 1,459 down and 519
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 721.29 million shares from 761.98
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
